<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actress Bids for U.S. Archery Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Geena Davis found out she was a good  
shot on a movie set. 
</P>
<P>
	The 43-year-old actress is now ranked 22nd in the nation in  
women's archery and is competing this weekend to qualify for the 
next Olympic team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have learned as an adult that I'm fairly athletic,'' Davis  
said Friday as she practiced for semifinals of the U.S. Olympic 
trials, which began this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The star of ``Thelma and Louise'' and ``The Accidental Tourist''  
-- for which she won an Oscar in 1988 -- has surprised archers with 
her quick rise in a sport that doesn't normally capture much 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Camera crews on Friday surrounded Davis, wearing a floppy blue  
hat and sunglasses, as she calmly fired off 60 arrows to a target 
70 meters away. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she would make the team, it would be unbelievable for our  
sport,'' said Denise Parker, the top-ranked woman in the nation. 
``The question is, does she want to be in the spotlight in this 
environment?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis discovered she had great aim while training to fire  
handguns for her part as an assassin in 1996's ``The Long Kiss 
Goodnight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She kept her hobby a secret from Hollywood and the public,  
despite winning a tournament or two, until she finished 29th out of 
300 women in Ohio to qualify for the Olympic semifinals. Four of 
the 32 semifinalists dropped out, making Davis one of 28 competing 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	That number will drop by Monday to eight women who will compete  
next month in California for three team spots and one alternate 
spot at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' coach Don Rabska, an archer for more than 30 years, said  
she has mastered a concentration during her acting career that 
helps her as an archer. Archery, he said, is all about finesse and 
mental toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis has been practicing five hours a day, shooting about 300  
arrows. She had a target range set up on the set of her latest 
film, ``Stuart Little.'' She also goes to the gym five days a week 
to work out on the treadmill and lift weights. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Davis: ``I don't feel that I've yet discovered how good I  
can get.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
