<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Seems Summerless With Cold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- For many residents of the Pacific Northwest, the  
only thing that gets them through them through the dark, dank 
winters is the promise of a bright, warm summer. 
</P>
<P>
	They're still waiting: This summer is the coolest in Seattle  
since 1956. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's complaining about it. ... It's a little  
depressing,'' said Ronnica Hamm, 32, working the deli counter at a 
grocery store. 
</P>
<P>
	The average high temperatures in June and July were 3 degrees to  
4 degrees below normal, while rainfall was slightly higher than 
usual. Seattle has had just two 80-degree days this month; last 
year, there had been seven by mid-month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually you can count on one really good month and we didn't  
even get that this year,'' said longtime local columnist Emmett 
Watson, now of The Seattle Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Some visitors from east of the Rockies -- where much of the  
country has been sweltering through heat and drought -- find it 
refreshing, but many locals are hurting. 
</P>
<P>
	``People feel cheated when they don't get a nice June,'' said  
Cliff Mass, a professor of atmospheric sciences at the University 
of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Mass is expecting sunshine in late August and September, but  
said the only remarkable weather this summer was the series of 
thunderstorms -- ``not only unusual but quite entertaining'' -- that 
marked the beginning of August. 
</P>
<P>
	Meteorologist Ted Buehner at the National Weather Service said  
residents are feeling ``ripped off'' by the cloudy, drizzly summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just got done with a La Nina winter that was really soggy,  
really windy and rather depressing,'' Buehner said. ``Now they're 
hearing that we're going to have La Nina again this winter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even plants are confused.  
</P>
<P>
	Local gardeners say plants are blooming out of their usual  
sequence and some magnolias and azaleas bloomed twice, said Carrie 
Bowman, who tends the Seattle Library gardens around the city. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Woodland Park Zoo, deputy director Mike Waller said June  
attendance was down 22 percent from last year and was ``probably 
the worst in our history.'' He said most people would rather see 
the zoo on a sunny day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to change that, since we have a series of indoor  
exhibits,'' Waller said. ``But if you're going to drag your kids in 
strollers, it's pretty uncomfortable to do that in the rain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buehner hasn't given up hope on summer, which doesn't officially  
begin here until July 12 and extends well into September. 
</P>
<P>
	Things look good this weekend, with a high near 80 forecast for  
Sunday. Still, Buehner said he's been a bit cautious about 
admitting his profession in some circles: ``They want to blame 
somebody.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
