<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 14:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parcells Not Happy With Jets Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Quarterback Rick Mirer takes the field  
for the Jets on Sunday afternoon. He may not like what he finds. 
</P>
<P>
	An irritated coach Bill Parcells again lashed into his ballclub  
Saturday, a day after enduring the team's listless performance in a 
10-9 preseason victory over the visiting Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	Players have been told to expect tougher practices and higher  
expectations, beginning Sunday when the Jets return to their 
Hofstra training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the more difficult things to explain to someone,  
but I can tell you I have seen this kind of behavior on a couple of 
other teams that I have had,'' Parcells said in a conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never really seen this kind of thing exist without a hard  
lesson having to be learned. I know if things don't change, if our 
team doesn't pick itself up, it will not be successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the game, the Jets announced that they had traded a  
conditional pick in next year's draft to the Packers for Mirer, 
expected to immediately step in as the main backup to starter Vinny 
Testaverde. Mirer, a former first-round pick who Parcells passed up 
in favor of Drew Bledsoe in the 1993 draft, met with Jets 
quarterbacks coach Dan Henning and Parcells Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have to see him, see where he is,'' Parcells  
said. ``We've got a lot of work to do with him before we put him in 
any situation. You've got to teach him what you want first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer may not be alone.  
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's game, played in occasionally heavy rain at Giants  
Stadium, Parcells saw his special teams and second-tier offensive 
and defensive units struggle for the second straight week. The Jets 
managed only 94 yards in the second half, failing to score, and 
found themselves fending off Eagles' threats too many times for 
comfort. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets, expected by many to contend for the AFC championship,  
are 1-1 in the preseason. Philadelphia, playing under first-year 
coach Andy Reid, fell to 0-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't play like we're capable of playing, like we want to  
be a Super Bowl team,'' Jets safety Victor Green said. ``We need 
more of a sense of urgency. If we keep coming out flat like we did 
... We just can't turn it on Sept. 12th (the season opener against 
the Patriots).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles rolled up 145 yards in kickoff and punt returns  
against the vaunted Jets' coverage units, gaining quality field 
position for much of the game. However, the Jets defense held the 
punchless Philadelphia offense to 220 yards, including 136 through 
the air, posting seven sacks, intercepting two throws and knocking 
down two passes by starting quarterback Doug Pederson. 
</P>
<P>
	The bright spot of that effort came with 9:58 left in the first  
half. The Eagles, set up at the Jets' 1-yard line when Leon Johnson 
muffed a punt, failed to punch the ball into the end zone, settling 
for Norm Johnson's 22-yard field goal, one of three scores for 
Johnson on the night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a kind of lackluster type of performance,'' Parcells  
said. ``But I think if I'm looking for something positive, the 
defense did respond well to the ball being on the 1-foot line and 
holding them to three points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other than that, we just didn't do very much.''  
</P>
<P>
	Jets backup quarterback Scott Zolak, told by a friend just  
before kickoff of the team's acquisition of Mirer, failed to rise 
to the occasion, completing just 10 of 22 passes for 90 yards and 
getting sacked three times. The Jets punted on all six possessions 
under Zolak. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
