<DOCNO> APW19990821.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 10:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Mork and Mindy' Actor in Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A once illustrious Manhattan gallery that helped  
launch Jackson Pollock and Willem de Kooning folds. And what, you 
may ask, does this have to do with the old TV show ``Mork and 
Mindy''? 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll Janis charges in a lawsuit that his brother, actor  
Conrad Janis, who played Mindy's dad on the 1970s sitcom, 
effectively looted the Sidney Janis Gallery started by their 
father, forcing it to close last month. 
</P>
<P>
	No way, says Conrad in a countersuit -- it was Carroll who looted  
and mismanaged the assets of their father, a onetime vaudeville 
dancer whose gallery off Fifth Avenue opened a half-century ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget Mork and Mindy. This is more like Cain and Abel.  
</P>
<P>
	In March, Carroll's suit claims, the 71-year-old Conrad  
``attempted to physically attack'' his 67-year-old brother -- a 
confrontation thwarted only when he ``was grabbed from behind'' and 
``physically restrained'' by his own assistant and his lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Their father, Sidney Janis, opened the gallery with his wife  
Harriet in 1948. He had a reputation for spotting trends, and in 
1961 mounted an exhibit that ushered in Pop Art. The father died in 
1989 at age 93, leaving most of his $200 million fortune to his two 
sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Pollock and de Kooning, their joint holdings include  
works by Albers, Motherwell, Oldenburg, Picasso, Braque, Klee, 
Leger, Dubuffet and Duchamp. 
</P>
<P>
	But things went sour, and their dispute came to state Supreme  
Court this week in dueling lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Conrad claims his younger brother overpaid himself, handed  
interest-free loans and art bargains to relatives and friends, made 
unauthorized contributions to charity and wouldn't give him the 
keys to the gallery or the access code to the burglar alarm. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll counters that he got stuck with all the work while  
Conrad traipsed off to Beverly Hills to pursue his acting career. 
He says Conrad enjoyed ``a free ride'' while abandoning 
responsibility for the gallery, which ``provided him with a 
handsome living for many years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All the while, says Carroll's suit, his brother caused the  
business ``enormous financial damages'' by spoiling the New York 
brother's reputation with ``baseless and scurrilous allegations'' 
during a weak art market in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	One work the brothers are quibbling over is the late Quaker  
painter Edward Hicks' ``The Peaceable Kingdom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For years, the sniping siblings had tried to settle things  
privately. Referred to in Conrad's suit as the ``management'' team 
of Carroll and Conrad, they even hired advisers to examine company 
finances from the time Carroll took over day-to-day operations in 
September 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides ``are attempting to amicably resolve their dispute,''  
says Conrad's lawyer, Brian Caplan. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mork and Mindy, Robin Williams played the space alien Mork  
from Ork, who was taken in by Mindy (Pam Dawber). Janis played 
Mindy's father. Mork and Mindy eventually marry and honeymoon on 
Ork, populated by bizarre creatures. 
</P>
<P>
	But this is no sitcom. Stay tuned to Carroll and Conrad.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones, Greene Set 100-Meter Paces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Marion Jones and Maurice Greene opened  
their bids for multiple gold medals with sensational times Saturday 
in the quarterfinals of the 100 meters at the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, seeking an unprecedented four golds, won her heat in a  
championship record 10.76 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, shooting for a rare sprint double and three golds, ran  
9.91, the sixth fastest time in the world this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' time shattered the previous championship record of 10.82  
set by fellow American Gail Devers in 1993 in Stuttgart. She also 
bettered her season's leading previous best of 10.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four women in history have run faster, including Jones, who  
posted 10.65 last year. The late Florence Griffith-Joyner still 
holds the world record of 10.49, set in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100 semifinals and finals are set for Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	After being called for a false start, Jones blew away the rest  
of the field as she solidified her status as the overwhelming 
favorite for the sprint title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't have asked for a better atmosphere, better  
weather,'' Jones said. ``The track is fast, fast, fast. Watch for 
some world records.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also qualifying for the semifinals in impressive style was  
American Inger Miller, who won her heat in a personal best 10.86, 
her first sub-11 since 1996. Greece's Ekaterini Thanos also ran 
10.86, a national record. 
</P>
<P>
	Others advancing included Devers and France's Christine Arron,  
both in 11 flat. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's 100, Greene clocked his seventh sub-10 race of the  
year and showed signs he may be set to threaten the world record of 
9.79 he set earlier this year in Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a very fast final,'' Greene said.  
``Everybody's predicting I'll break (the record). We'll have to 
wait and see about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene outran one of his top rivals, Canada's Bruny Surin, who  
clocked 9.95. 
</P>
<P>
	``My coach (John Smith) told me, `Show 'em a little bit, but  
don't show 'em all of it,''' said Greene, who is also competing in 
the 200 and 400 relay. ``I believe I did that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others winning their heats were Obadele Thompson of Barbados  
(10.04), Jason Gardener of Britain (10.04), Dwain Chambers of 
Britain (10.08) and Namibia's Frankie Fredericks (10.09). 
</P>
<P>
	The first gold medal of the championships went to Russia's Ilya  
Markov, who won the men's 20-kilometer walk in 1 hour, 23.34. 
Olympic champion Jefferson Perez of Ecuador took the silver, 45 
seconds behind, while defending champion Daniel Garcia of Spain was 
third, another 12 seconds back. 
</P>
<P>
	The versatile Jones also advanced to the final of the long jump.  
She is seeking gold medals in the 100, 200, long jump and a relay. 
</P>
<P>
	In the long jump, Jones leaped 22 feet, 4 1-4 inches on her  
second attempt, a distance that automatically put her into Monday's 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the most confident I've been all year (in the long jump)  
and pleased that I could get through qualifying on the second 
jump,'' Jones said. ``My rhythm is a lot better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The best long jump qualifier was Italy's Fiona May, the 1995  
world champion. May soared 23 feet, 1 1-4 inches, the second-best 
jump in the world this year, on her first try. 
</P>
<P>
	A third American attempting to win multiple medals, John Godina,  
began his bid for a third straight shot put title, qualifying for 
Saturday night's final with a heave of 67 feet, 10 3-4 inches, the 
best of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Toth, also of the U.S., had the second-best qualifying  
throw, 67 feet, 4 inches, and the other two Americans, Andy Bloom 
and C.J. Hunter, Jones' husband, also made the shot put final. 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's opening event of the heptathlon, the 100 hurdles,  
France's Eunice Barber, the European champion, made a strong 
impression, winning her heat in a personal-best 12.89 seconds. The 
next-fastest time among the 22 competitors was 13.28 by U.S. 
champion Shelia Burrell. 
</P>
<P>
	Another American, Tiffany Lott-Hogan, was disqualified for two  
false starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Barber had another career-best in the second event, clearing  
1.93 meters (6-4), for a total of 2,286 points and a 185-point lead 
over runner-up Denise Lewis of Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	There were some big surprises in the men's hammer throw  
qualifying. Among those failing to reach Sunday's final were the 
1-2 finishers at the 1996 Olympics, Balazs Kiss of Hungary and 
Lance Deal of the United States, along with Uzbekistan's Andrey 
Abduvaliyev, the 1992 Olympic gold medalist and 1993 and 1995 world 
champion, and Russia's Vasilly Sidorenko, the 1997 world bronze 
medalist. 
</P>
<P>
	Karsten Kobs of Germany had the longest qualifying throw,  
258-10. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one thing could have stolen the stage Saturday from the  
world's No. 1 sprinters: the revelation of a drug case involving 
yet another big star. 
</P>
<P>
	A string of positive tests involving some of athletics' biggest  
names -- Merlene Ottey, Javier Sotomayor, Linford Christie and 
Dennis Mitchell -- had dulled some of the anticipation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last couple of weeks our beautiful and lovely sport  
has been marred by all of this,'' said Jones, unbeaten since 1997 
in the two sprints. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that our wonderful performances will overshadow what  
has happened.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
