<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irvan Upgraded From Fair to Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Ernie Irvan, who sustained a bruised lung  
and a mild head injury in a crash at Michigan Speedway, was listed 
in good condition Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, doctors at St. Joseph Mercy Hospital in nearby Ypsilanti,  
who has listed Irvan's condition as fair after the crash Friday, 
decided to keep him until at least Sunday to run a few more tests 
on the injured NASCAR Winston Cup star. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Cameron, public relations director for the speedway, said  
Irvan's family had decided not to grant interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan, injured five years to the day after a near-fatal wreck on  
the same track will be replaced Sunday in the Pepsi 400 by Dick 
Trickle. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan, 40, was knocked unconscious in the crash in turn 4 during  
a Busch Grand National practice session, but became responsive as 
he was being transported to the infield medical center. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers trying to get Irvan out had to cut the roof from his  
car. He appeared to lose control of his Pontiac and spun in turn 4 
on the banked 2-mile oval. The rear quarter panel struck the 
concrete wall before the driver's side made contact. 
</P>
<P>
	As he was removed from the car, Irvan appeared to pick his arm  
up in what looked like a wave. 
</P>
<P>
	When Irvan crashed in turn 2 during Winston Cup practice on Aug.  
20, 1994, he was unconscious for two days. Irvan had critical brain 
and chest injuries. He was given only a 10-percent chance of 
survival. 
</P>
<P>
	But he returned to the Winston Cup circuit on Oct. 1, 1995, in  
North Wilkesboro, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan had planned to compete in both the Busch Series race  
Saturday and the Winston Cup event. He co-owns the Busch car, and 
is in his second year driving the Winston Cup car for MB2 
Motorsports. Last month, Irvan's contract was extended through the 
end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan has 15 Winston Cup victories, but none since taking the  
June race at Michigan in 1997. He is 26th this year in the 
standings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
