<HEADLINE> A's Put Chavez on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Rookie third baseman Eric Chavez was  
placed on the 15-day disabled list Saturday with a right foot 
injury, and the Oakland Athletics recalled outfielder Jason 
McDonald. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez was hurt during an 11-0 loss to Toronto on Friday when he  
tried to avoid being tagged at first base and his foot landed 
awkwardly on the bag. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury was diagnosed as plantar fascia, a tearing of the  
membrane in the back of the foot. He's expected to be sidelined at 
least three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, who was hitting .259, was playing well for the A's after  
a slow start. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the All-Star break, Chavez was hitting .324 with six home  
runs and he was tied for the AL lead among third baseman with a 
.958 fielding percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland manager Art Howe said Olmedo Saenz and Scott Spiezio  
will split time at third in Chavez's absence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that Spiezio and Saenz will do a nice job for us at  
third,'' Howe said. ``We're certainly going to miss Chavez because 
he was doing so well for us. He had nice range and played very 
solid third base for us. He solidified the lower part of our order, 
gave us some power there. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other two guys are going to have to step in, give us  
quality at bats and play as solid as they can at third. I'm sure 
they both can because they've shown us they can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald was optioned to Double-A Midland on Wednesday when the  
A's acquired Rich Becker in a trade with Milwaukee. However, he was 
recalled before he appeared in a game for Midland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to be here, obviously,'' said McDonald, who began  
his third tour with the A's this season. ``The team was doing well 
and I wanted to be up here and be a part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, walking around the club house on crutches, said he  
suffered a similar foot injury last year while he was in the minor 
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, it bothered me for about six weeks but this one  
doesn't feel as bad,'' Chavez said. ``I want to make it back as 
soon as I can but it might take me the whole three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just have to stay off it. They said the only thing that can  
heal this is time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
