<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans of Kitsch Tour Cultural Icons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The tackier the better for these folks.  
</P>
<P>
	In the city that brought America sacks of little square  
hamburgers sold in porcelain steel White Castles, nostalgic fans of 
commercial kitsch met this weekend to discuss the historical 
significance of eye-catching roadside design. 
</P>
<P>
	In spirit at least, the electric buzz of old neon was in the air  
as members of the Society for Commercial Archeology shared their 
passion for preserving familiar and forgotten monuments to American 
culture, especially the gaudy ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me personally, nothing is too over-the-top,'' said  
participant Bert Bedeau, who works at the Idaho State Historic 
Preservation Office in Boise. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides classic White Castle burger joints, made to look like  
miniature medieval fortresses, the society was drawn to Columbus 
for its wealth of vintage motels and fast-food restaurants, 
roadside businesses whose main marketing goal was to get drivers to 
pull over. 
</P>
<P>
	The society is made up of architects, designers, teachers,  
collectors and others who simply have a taste for 20th century 
power marketing, said Daniel Hershberger of Plymouth, Mich., 
society president. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's bus tour agenda Saturday included a stop at the  
headquarters of White Castle, which sells little square burgers by 
the sack at about 330 restaurants, mostly in the Midwest and the 
East. 
</P>
<P>
	Company founders began experimenting with steel buildings in the  
'20s because they were easy to maintain and simple to dismantle and 
move, a necessity in still-developing urban areas. They settled on 
steel covered with white porcelain enamel. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're looking at is one of the earliest trademark  
buildings. This is a building designed, essentially, to be a 
three-dimensional logo,'' Hershberger said. ``It's a hamburger 
restaurant, but it's made to look like a castle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all society members agree fast-food is worth commemorating,  
as the group did with a kick-off reception at the flagship Wendy's 
hamburger restaurant. Large fast-food chains helped force oldtime 
diners and owner-operated lunch counters that the society reveres 
out of business, said Nancy Sturm, a fund-raiser for the National 
Endowment for the Humanities in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I might visit a White Castle because it speaks of the region,  
but a place like Wendy's that has national penetration doesn't 
thrill me,'' Ms. Sturm said. 
</P>
<P>
	The original Wendy's, located in a downtown building that had  
once housed a car dealership, opened in 1969. It now features a 
museum detailing the history of Wendy's International Inc., which 
has 5,300 outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	Another society fascination is old motels. Dozens still stand  
between downtown Columbus and Newark, about 30 miles to the east. 
Most went out of business during the 1960s, but society members 
collect and photograph the distinctive artwork of their colorful 
signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems there are about 11,000 places called the Sands  
Motel,'' said Ed Dorsa, an associate professor of industrial design 
at Virginia Tech University in Blacksburg, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	He actually had pictures of just three, along with dozens of  
neon signs he photographed in the Southwest and during a 
cross-country trip. He was looking for ideas to publish his 
pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	The society, which is funded through member dues and corporate  
sponsorship, strives to raise public awareness about what's left of 
urban curbside commerce that was abandoned for freeways and 
suburban mini-malls, said Christian Overland of Dearborn, who works 
at the Ford museum. 
</P>
<P>
	It works with other organizations that have similar goals and  
members who also often feels left out by higher profile groups that 
fight to preserve more famous landmarks, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're bringing groups together who thought they were by  
themselves,'' Overland said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
