<HEADLINE> Former Va. Governor Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Federal authorities are investigating L.  
Douglas Wilder's use of money left over from his 1990 inauguration 
as the nation's first elected black governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am currently in discussion with federal tax authorities on  
matters relating to my inaugural fund,'' Wilder said in a statement 
Friday. ``I am cooperating fully and have instructed my accountants 
and anyone else who might have relevant information to do 
likewise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilder said his attorney advised him not to comment further.  
</P>
<P>
	Wilder, governor from 1990 to 1994, was questioned about the  
inaugural fund for most of his term. A ball held on the night of 
his historic inauguration took in $1.8 million and netted $966,533. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilder said he would use the money for personal political  
expenses and to help state candidates; he donated $50,000 to the 
state Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax experts said at the time that if the money went for personal  
use, he would have to pay taxes on it. 
  	   	
</P>
