<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Restaurant Popular in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- On a dark, steep street, just off Hong Kong's  
trendy Mid-levels area, about two dozen people gather in a small 
bar and ask for Mr. Lau. 
</P>
<P>
	They wait, chatting and looking around at the others who are  
probably there for the same reason. After a few drinks, Lau Kin Wai 
appears and tells the crowd it's time to go. Then he walks them up 
the road to an unmarked yellow door. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems like a secret society, but it's actually a bunch of  
strangers gathering for dinner at Sichuan Cuisine Da Ping Huo -- one 
of the hottest eating venues in Hong Kong. The fact that it doesn't 
have a restaurant license or a telephone listing doesn't seem to be 
a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	From its unassuming entrance, Da Ping Huo is a far cry from  
traditional restaurants, which lure their customers off the streets 
with a riot of neon lights, tanks of live fish and gilded statues 
of Chinese deities. 
</P>
<P>
	Lau, an art critic and one of the founders of Da Ping Huo, is  
quick to explain how his business is different from others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't call this a restaurant,'' he says. ``It's just  
everyone giving a little money to eat dinner.'' The proprietors 
also don't pay taxes on what they make from the dinners, which cost 
$26 per head, Lau says, breaking from his generally staid demeanor 
to giggle. And in terms of profits, well, they just about break 
even, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Da Ping Huo originated when Lau, his Sichuan artist friend, Wang  
Hai, and Wang's wife, Wong Siu-king, decided to split Wong's food 
costs by cooking dinners for friends. 
</P>
<P>
	They invited the owners of a struggling furniture store into  
their dinner club, and began serving meals a few times a week at 
the furniture store. 
</P>
<P>
	Word spread quickly through Lau's art circles about the place  
and its homemade, spicy cuisine from China's southwest. Notables, 
such as opposition legislator Martin Lee and tycoon Richard Li, 
started showing up, Lau said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few months, the trio ventured out and found the tiny,  
two-room place in Mid-levels. They began serving 12-course set-menu 
meals that include Sichuan classics, such as spicy tofu and 
stir-fried beans with minced pork. Sichuan is a province in 
southwestern China known for -- among other things -- spicy food. 
</P>
<P>
	Da Ping Huo maintains its unlicensed business with no problems,  
even getting reviewed by several local newspapers. Government 
officials, celebrities and business people continue to be among its 
patrons. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole fact that it's private, the quality is better.  
You're not getting restaurant food,'' says Henry Lee, who once 
waited two weeks to get his table at Da Ping Huo. Now, people wait 
up to four months, putting their names on a list that Lau keeps 
scribbled on a few folded pages in his pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	And as long as Da Ping Huo doesn't open loud doors to the  
public, Hong Kong's Urban Services Department has been told the 
eatery is used for private parties and so is OK to operate, says a 
department spokeswoman on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the dinner group's success, Lau says there are no plans  
to expand and legitimize the venture any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Wong, who cooks every dish herself on three household burners in  
the back room, doesn't think she could handle more customers. ``I 
just wouldn't feel right about letting anyone else do the 
cooking,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	The food so impressed Lau's friend Annabel Jackson, the head of  
public relations at the five-star Mandarin Oriental that she 
arranged for Wong to cook there once a week as part of a rustic 
Chinese cuisine food promotion. The hotel charges twice the price 
for the same Da Ping Huo fare. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was eating at the tiny, hidden local dining spot that  
fascinates Henry Lee. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole fact that it's private, the quality is better,'' Lee  
said. ``You're not getting restaurant food.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
