<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Helps Catch Escaped Murderer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENDENHALL, Pa. (AP) -- Rick Mercurio likes to joke around, so  
fiancee Ellen Baldo didn't believe him when he said an escaped 
killer was lurking near their house. 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't joking. Before long, their morning turned into  
something resembling a crime thriller, with frightening noises from 
their back deck, a scramble to snatch up a gun and cellular phones, 
a dash to safety in their barn and flashlight signals to police 
helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	The search for convicted murderer Norman Johnston ended early  
Friday in the couple's front yard. 
</P>
<P>
	A wet, scratched and exhausted Johnston, who killed four  
teen-agers to cover up a family burglary ring, was captured not far 
from where he and his brothers committed their crimes two decades 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston was sentenced to life in prison in 1980 along with  
older brothers Bruce Sr. and David. The men feared the teens would 
tell police about their activities. The 1978 slayings were 
portrayed in the film ``At Close Range'' starring Sean Penn. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston, 48, had been on the run since Aug. 2, when he escaped  
from a maximum-security prison in Huntington, 130 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	The dramatic capture began after Mercurio, who is in the  
wholesale produce business, left for work about 4 a.m. Friday. He 
came back a few minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Baldo described what happened next: ``He headed downstairs  
to open up the safe and he was getting his gun out of the safe, at 
the same time saying to me, `The house is surrounded. The property 
is surrounded by police. Norman Johnston is in the woods.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't believe him at first,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The two knew the hunt for Johnston had heated up after he  
crashed a car late Thursday less than two miles from their house. 
</P>
<P>
	All through the night, Ms. Baldo said, ``it was choppers and  
police.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mercurio got his gun -- and then the noises started.  
</P>
<P>
	It was ``like somebody was underneath the back deck knocking  
something over, or walking into something,'' Ms. Baldo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grabbing the gun, flashlights and two cellular phones, the two  
hurried to their barn and called 911. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing that there were choppers in the valley, he said to the  
operator on 911, `I'll signal you with the flashlight so that you 
can get closer to the house ... we'll stay in the barn, so if you 
pick up anything in or around the house it's probably him,''' Ms. 
Baldo said. 
</P>
<P>
	After spotting the flashlight signal, police soon located the  
house and fanned out to search under the deck. The couple then 
spotted Johnston as he emerged from some trees in front of the 
house. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's Norman,'' Mercurio yelled.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnston turned and ran, crashed into a board fence in the  
bushes, and police grabbed him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he was kind of surprised to see us,'' said Trooper  
Brian Barber. ``He was tired. He knew it was daylight. He knew he 
didn't have any place left to run.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
