<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Little League Team Goes for Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Just getting to the Little League World  
Series is difficult enough. But the team from Toms River, N.J. is 
trying to defend its title. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey team becomes the third team in 52 years to return  
to the series for 11- and 12-year-olds. Lock Haven, Pa., won in 
1948 and came back in 1949, and Long Beach, Calif., won in 1991 
when a team from the Philippines was disqualified, and then won the 
championship outright the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think most people realize how amazing it is,'' said  
Red Gaynor, grandfather of Toms River pitcher Casey Gaynor and 
father of manager Mike Gaynor. ``You have better odds at winning 
Powerball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Gaynor becomes the first person to manage three teams at  
the series, each of them during the last five years. His son, 
Casey, threw a no-hitter during the regional playoffs, and Eric 
Campesi hit a home run in Thursday's regional final 3-0 win over 
Middleboro, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting Casey and Eric made a huge difference. They expect to  
win,'' second baseman Mike Casale said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both played as 11-year-olds with last year's champions -- only  
the seventh U.S. team to win the series during the last 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Toms River plays Phenix City, Ala., at 6 p.m. Sunday in an  
opening round. Phenix City manager Tony Rasmus said his ``scrawny 
bunch'' exceeded most expectations -- he would have been happy 
enough being on national television for the southern final, a 3-2 
win over Kernersville, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Colby, will pitch against Toms River.  
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Brownsburg, Ind., plays Phenix City and Toms River  
plays Boise, Idaho -- only the fourth team from outside California 
to represent the western United States since Gerald Ford's 
administration. Boise's Dane McCrady, also a manager's son, threw a 
two-hitter in a 3-1 regional championship win over Sacramento, 
Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan, whose teams have won the series 17 times in that span,  
is absent. Osaka, Japan, a U.S. team from Ramstein Air Force Base 
in Germany, Victoria, British Columbia and Yabucoa, Puerto Rico are 
also in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	One team each will emerge from the U.S. and international  
divisions for Thursday night's semifinals. Within a division, the 
teams all play each other, and the team with the best record before 
Thursday advances. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship is set for 4:30 p.m. EDT Saturday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 14:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Papis Gets CART Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- Winning the pole for the inaugural Target  
Grand Prix brought a feeling of contentment that Max Papis has 
missed in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was driving for Ferrari, I got kind of used to being on  
the pole,'' Papis said after topping Saturday's qualifying on the 
1-mile oval at the new Chicago Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really missed the feeling. It's a personal satisfaction. The  
race tomorrow is what is important, but winning the pole position 
means today I'm the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pole was the first in 54 CART FedEx Series races for the  
29-year-old Italian driver. It was also his first since 1996, when 
Papis was running in World Sports Cars for Ferrari. 
</P>
<P>
	Papis, who moved up the grid when he took over the Team Rahal  
seat left vacant when team owner Bobby Rahal retired from the 
cockpit after last season, turned a lap of 162.559 mph. That was 
just enough to relegate Mark Blundell's 162.381 to the outside of 
the front row for Sunday's 225-lap race. 
</P>
<P>
	Papis, who nearly got his first victory last month at Michigan  
Speedway before running out of fuel while leading the race on the 
last lap, said a combination of things have brought him toward the 
top of the pack in the second half of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing has changed,'' he said. ``I'm always the same. You  
have it in your heart or you don't. It's the team around you that 
brings out the best in you. They motivate me and I motivate them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On ovals, CART's qualifying procedure sends the drivers onto the  
track one at a time, in order from slowest to fastest in the 
combined practices leading up to time trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell, something of a surprise after showing little speed in  
practice, had been at the top of the speed chart for quite a while 
before Papis, the fastest in practice, drove his Reynard-Ford onto 
the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a tinge of disappointment that we didn't get the pole,''  
said Blundell, whose lap time was just 0.025-seconds slower than 
that of Papis. ``It would have been my first CART pole, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former series champion Jimmy Vasser was third at 162.331,  
followed by series points leader Dario Franchitti at 162.296, Helio 
Castro-Neves at 162.246 and Patrick Carpentier at 161.884. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Montoya, Vasser's teammate and trailing Franchitti by just  
one point in the season standings, was 10th at 160.357. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a good car, but not a qualifying car,'' said Montoya,  
a rookie who leads the series with five victories this season. 
``I'm still excited about the race. The track has improved quite a 
bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Andretti, third in the standings and 28 points behind,  
was even farther back in 18th after qualifying at just 156.906. 
</P>
<P>
	A big question heading into Sunday's race is whether the new  
track will lend itself to passing. So far, with limited rubber laid 
down on the track, most of the passing has occurred under braking 
in turns 1 and 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a fresh track, a little like a golf course,'' Blundell  
said. ``It needs to mature. It has to have people go around it and 
build up rubber. And with the hard braking on this track, it's 
going to be hard to keep brakes under you for 225 laps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what kind of a race he expects it to be, Papis said,  
``It's going to be flat out. It's a short oval.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
