<HEADLINE> Family Misidentifies Girl's Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) -- A girl whose body was recovered from Lake  
Michigan was misidentified as her older sister by relatives 
distraught over the loss of the girls and their father on a family 
sailing trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Bull, 39, and his two daughters, Madeleine and Alexandra,  
were reported missing Monday after they failed to return from an 
overnight trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Two bodies recovered Wednesday were identified by family members  
from photographs as Bull and 7-year-old Madeleine. Family friend 
Amy Falk said the body was actually that of Madeleine's 5-year-old 
sister. 
</P>
<P>
	The mistake was discovered Friday during funeral arrangements.  
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard officials have called off their search for the other  
girl. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-foot sailboat was found in good condition Tuesday about  
27 miles from shore, and authorities said the only thing out of the 
ordinary was that the swim ladder was down in the water. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were found a few hundred yards apart, without life  
jackets, 20 miles southwest of the boat. Authorities said the 
victims had drowned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd have to speculate, but it is likely that someone ... fell  
overboard, and then they jumped in after,'' Coast Guard Lt. Chris 
Button said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bull was chairman of Bradner Central Co., a family-owned firm  
that distributes business forms and other paper products. He and 
his wife, Pam, also have an infant son. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
