<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astros Win 'Ugly' Game Over Marlins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The pitching staff's totals for the 16-inning game  
-- 21 strikeouts, 17 walks, 299 pitches -- looked like something from 
a high school team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Marlins have been called worse.  
</P>
<P>
	Florida had the Houston Astros swinging and missing as if Kerry  
Wood was on the mound, but the Marlins still managed to lose 6-4 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros stranded 20 runners in the ugly marathon. They didn't  
manage a hit in extra innings until the 16th, when Ken Caminiti's 
second homer of the night broke a 4-4 tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a nutsy game,'' Caminiti said. ``But it's a win, and we  
love it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the Marlins, their 72nd loss of the season stood out from  
the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This seems like the toughest one for me,'' manager John Boles  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida stranded 21 runners and lost despite out-hitting Houston  
15-7. The Astros had more homers (three) than singles (two). 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference is they know how to win these kind of games,  
and we're learning,'' Marlins catcher Mike Redmond said. 
</P>
<P>
	The game took 5 hours, 44 minutes, the longest by time in  
Marlins' history. It matched Arizona's 7-6 win over Los Angeles on 
April 13 as the longest by innings in the major leagues this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida starter Ryan Dempster set the tone for the wild night  
with eight strikeouts and seven walks in 3 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ridiculous,'' he said. ``Walks are a pain in the butt.''  
</P>
<P>
	The 17 bases on balls issued by Dempster and six successors were  
a Marlins record, and also a record for Houston hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Bagwell went 0-for-2 and walked six times, tying a  
major-league record first achieved by Jimmie Foxx of Boston in 
1938. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not really the record I'm looking for,'' Bagwell said. ``It  
was a crazy game. But it's nice to play 16 when you win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros' strikeout total broke the team record of 20 set  
against Wood last year. It was a record for Marlins pitching, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston's seven pitchers included Billy Wagner, who earned his  
31st save. Manager Larry Dierker considered using starter Mike 
Hampton as a pinch hitter, but the left-hander left during the game 
when his wife went into labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Caminiti hit a third-inning homer, his first in nearly four  
months. Then, 13 innings later, he hit another one. He returned 
from the disabled list Monday after missing 79 games with a calf 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone was going up there trying to end it with one  
swing,'' Caminiti said. ``I was really tired as the game went on. 
But it was the first game where I really had a good time and 
enjoyed myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Craig Biggio didn't have quite so much fun. He went  
1-for-8 with four strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I know is I'm just glad we won,'' Biggio said. ``I was  
thinking, `This could be a really bad day.''' 
</P>
<P>
	For Florida, it was. The Marlins rallied from a 4-0 deficit,  
then were shut out over the final seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
	With their bench depleted, pitcher Alex Fernandez pinch-hit with  
the bases loaded in the 11th. He flied out to the warning track to 
end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours later, Dempster stood in the losing clubhouse and  
looked at the clock. It said 1 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``This one's over,'' he said. ``It's a new day already.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
