<HEADLINE> 2 Pirates Put on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates put two of their five  
starting pitchers, Todd Ritchie and Pete Schourek, on the disabled 
list Saturday and activated left-handers Jason Christiansen and 
Chris Peters. 
</P>
<P>
	Schourek, a $4 million free agent pickup who has disappointed  
the Pirates with a 3-7 record and 5.68 ERA, has inflammation in his 
left shoulder. He will be replaced in the rotation by rookie Jimmy 
Anderson, who started Saturday night against Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates have had 19 players on the disabled list this  
season, or only six players fewer than an entire 25-man roster. 
They currently have nine on the list, including catcher Jason 
Kendall, starting shortstop Pat Meares, former closer Rich Loiselle 
and Ritchie, their top winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritchie's injury -- tendinitis in his rotator cuff -- is a major  
blow to the Pirates, who are contending for their first winning 
season since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritchie (12-8) leads the Pirates in victories despite never  
starting in the majors before this season. He took advantage of 
Peters' early-season arm problems to win a spot in the rotation and 
has been Pittsburgh's most consistent starter, pitching into the 
seventh inning in nine of his last 10 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritchie reported pain in his pitching shoulder while beating the  
Diamondbacks 5-4 Friday night, yielding five runs -- two after he 
left the game -- and four hits in 6 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritchie had retired 14 batters in a row until leaving after  
Erubiel Durazo's single and Steve Finley's double in the seventh 
inning. The shoulder began bothering him several starts ago, but he 
pitched through the pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been building up, and I may need a little rest,'' said  
Ritchie, a non-roster player in spring training who did not make 
the opening day roster. ``It might be that my muscles are not used 
to throwing so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The injury may keep Ritchie, 27, from winning 15 or 16 games in  
his first season as a major league starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to shut it down for a while and try to get it  
right,'' he said. ``When you look at the big picture, you have to 
be cautious so I can keep on pitching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peters was 8-10 with a 3.97 ERA in 1998 and was in the rotation  
until developing inflammation in his left shoulder. He was 1-1 with 
a 6.88 ERA in 12 games before going on the disabled list in early 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters spent time at Triple-A Nashville on a rehabilitation  
assignment, stopped pitching for a while when he reported 
discomfort, then resumed the rehabilitation assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last appearance at Nashville, he beat Omaha 4-1 on  
Thursday, allowing one run on three hits despite walking five in 
seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Peters will start Wednesday against Colorado.  
</P>
<P>
	Christiansen (2-3, 4.46 ERA) had a 10.38 ERA in his final 12  
games before going on the disabled list July 31 with lower back 
inflammation. With Christiansen out, Scott Sauerbeck was the 
Pirates' only left-handed reliever. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
