<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dragila Wins Women's Pole Vault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Winning gold medals by matching world  
records in historic firsts is becoming a habit for Stacy Dragila. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila, a 28-year-old former rodeo competitor, won the first  
gold medal to be awarded in the women's pole vault at an outdoor 
world championship on Saturday and in the process equaled the world 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	The American cleared 15 feet, 1 inch to beat Anzhela Balakhonova  
of Ukraine, who took the silver medal at 14-11, a European record 
in the event that was contested for the first time in a world 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila trailed the Ukrainian all the way until she scaled 15-1  
on her second attempt. That matched the world record set by 
Australia's Emma George on Feb. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted that mark and I was hungry for some more marks but I  
am glad I came ahead and won the gold,'' Dragila said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila made three attempts to extend the record to 15-3, but  
missed them all. 
</P>
<P>
	Tatiana Grigorieva, a Russian-born vaulter now competing for  
Australia, won the bronze at 14-7 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila, a former heptathlete and volleyball player, completed  
an historic double. 
</P>
<P>
	She won the 1997 world indoor title by equaling the then-world  
record of 14-5 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really haven't thought about it like that. I came here with  
a plan, I wanted to jump high and I wanted to be on the podium,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila had cleared 15 feet earlier this year, but on a wooden  
runaway that is not recognized by the international athletics body. 
</P>
<P>
	She had a stress fracture in her foot last year and underwent  
surgery in September, coming back in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I am a good healer or the injury wasn't as bad as we  
thought,'' she said. ``I'm just glad I'm back in full force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dragila now has to see whether she will get the full $60,000 for  
the gold medal normally awarded to world championship winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Because women's pole vault is a new event, she may end up  
getting only $30,000, although IAAF officials will later rule if 
she is eligible for the full award. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of unfortunate.'' Dragila said. ``I think we've been  
established since 1997. I think we deserve it. At the Olympics next 
year I hope we don't get half a medal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's pole vault competition provided a thrilling end to  
the first day of the championship and lasted more than four hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Balakhonova cleared all her jumps on the first attempt up to  
14-11. But she failed two times at 15-1 and once at 15-3 and 
settled for the silver. 
</P>
<P>
	George, the Commonwealth champion coming off a recent back  
injury in a training accident, failed to clear 14-3 1/4 after 
struggling throughout the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian has set 17 world records outdoors and indoors.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
