<HEADLINE> Hawaiian Luau Canceled at Dartmouth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- A Hawaiian luau at Dartmouth College was  
canceled after students complained it was culturally insensitive. 
</P>
<P>
	The party, sponsored by the Alpha Chi Alpha fraternity and the  
Delta Delta Delta sorority, was to be held last weekend. It was 
canceled after a student sent an e-mail message to everyone on 
campus describing it as an act of ``bigotry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another student Aaron Akamu, a native of Hawaii, criticized the  
luau in the student newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``That people feel a right to capitalize on some stereotype of  
where I am from and the people I feel a cultural responsibility to 
in the name of fun, angers and hurts me,'' Akamu wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hawaii, a luau is a large feast with a religious theme. But  
with the growth of tourism on the islands, the luau has come to 
resemble more of a beach party. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second time in a year that a party with an ethnic  
theme has caused an uproar on the Ivy League campus. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, more than 400 Dartmouth students staged a peaceful  
protest against a fraternity-sorority sponsored ``ghetto'' party in 
which students were encouraged to dress as inner-city black people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
