<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fittipaldi Hopes To Race Texaco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- Christian Fittipaldi, knocked unconscious in  
a crash during testing at Gateway International Raceway earlier 
this month, hopes to resume racing Sept. 26 at the Texaco Grand 
Prix of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	If not, the 28-year-old driver will wait three more weeks for  
the Hondo Indy 300 in Queensland, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can't drive the car, I'll just sit on the beach and enjoy  
myself,'' Fittipaldi said Saturday, showing a sense of humor as he 
attended the Target Grand Prix at Chicago Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Fittipaldi hit a wall during his practice run in Madison, Ill.,  
and was unconscious for between five and 10 minutes. Tests show 
that the nephew of longtime racing star Emerson Fittipaldi has a 
subdural hematoma -- a collection of blood -- on the left side of his 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having very little headaches, almost nothing,'' said  
Fittipaldi, who will have to be cleared by doctors before he can 
get back on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just watching some races and getting revved up to come  
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *--------	 
</P>
<P>
	BAD TIMING: This isn't the way Tony Bettenhausen dreamed of  
racing in his own backyard. Born and reared in nearby Tinley Park, 
CART team owner Bettenhausen had long noted the absence of a major 
motor speedway in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's past due that this part of the country had a  
speedway,'' Bettenhausen said Saturday before qualifying began for 
Sunday's 225-mile Target Grand Prix. But if only the track had been 
ready a year ago, when Bettenhausen had a team that at least could 
compete with CART's best cars and drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Or if only the track had not opened until next year, when he  
hopes he can get back on the developmental track that gave his team 
six podium finishes over an eight-year period. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the loss of his sponsor has forced him to run a raw  
rookie, Shigeaki Hattori, who has brought sponsorship money but, so 
far, not a single championship point, to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a real steep learning curve for Hattori,''  
Bettenhausen said. ``We haven't been able to go testing, and that's 
a tough deal. (Rookie Cristiano) da Matta had 3,000 miles of 
testing before he ever ran a race for Arciero-Wells.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bettenhausen has run rookie drivers before, including Helio  
Castro-Neves, who had a pole and a second-place finish last year. 
But Bettenhausen felt obligated to release the young Brazilian from 
the final two years of his contract when his sponsorship fell 
apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the resources we had last year and with Helio we'd have  
won races this year,'' Bettenhausen said. ``We've been running 
year-old Reynards all season, and it's hard to be competitive that 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bettenhausen is trying hard to get a new major sponsor, but  
failure breeds failure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard when you're in the back of the pack,'' he said.  
``What do you tell them when they ask how you're doing this 
year?'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BIG MOUTH: Max Papis might have learned a lesson all race  
drivers should heed. When you've got a secret, keep it that way. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked after Friday's practice how he liked the new one-mile  
oval, Papis, who was the second fastest driver Friday and quickest 
in Saturday morning's practice, responded: ``I love that there are 
no curbs out there, only the white line. If someone is in front of 
you suddenly, you have a place to go below the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore. CART officials fired off a bulletin Saturday  
morning to the effect that any driver who gets his right side tires 
on or over the white line will be penalized. In qualifying, no time 
would be given for a lap in which the driver was in violation. 
During the race a black flag drive-through penalty will be 
imposed. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	ALMOST THERE: Mark Blundell still has not fully recovered from  
the broken collarbone he suffered in a testing crash in May, but 
thinks Sunday's race on an oval track could be easier on him than 
his first two comeback events on road circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's little easier because you can build up the head rests a  
little bit,'' Blundell said. ``But, on the other hand, there is 
constant G force and on this oval a lot of braking, so your head 
goes forward. I'm not up to 100 percent yet, but it won't be too 
much longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell spent several minutes Saturday morning talking with  
Formula One team owner Frank Williams, a guest this week of CART 
car owner Chip Ganassi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was Frank's first test driver,'' Blundell recalled. ``I was  
his test driver for two years before Damon (Hill) got the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is the current employer of Alex Zanardi, who won two  
PPG Cup points titles driving for Ganassi. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganassi was the guest of Williams during a Formula One event  
earlier this year in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PRECAUTIONARY TESTS: Boris Derichebourg, who hit the wall in  
turn 2 during Saturday morning's Indy Lights practice, was taken to 
Loyola Medical Center for precautionary x-rays and observaton. 
Derichebourg was diagnosed with a minor concussion by CART medical 
director Dr. Steve Olvey during a preliminary exam at the track. No 
driver is permitted to compete for at least seven days following an 
accident that results in a concussion or loss of consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	FAN APPRECIATION:The final weekend of the 1999 CART series in  
Fontana, Calif., has been designated as fan appreciation weekend. 
The race, which could determine the PPG Cup points champion, will 
be run Oct. 31. The winner takes home $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	CART, the California Speedway and seven corporate partners  
joined forces for the fan appreciation events and a prize contest 
that includes an around-the-world trip to four continents to attend 
CART races next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
