<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Domenici Promotes GOP Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republicans' $792 billion package of tax  
cuts is the party's way of refunding money that citizens have 
overpaid, Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining the Republican chorus pushing the 10-year-plan, the New  
Mexico Republican said in the party's weekly radio address that 
``the government is taking more money from you than it needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A projected surplus over the next decade would leave $1.5  
trillion to give back to taxpayers, even after most of the money is 
reserved to strengthen Social Security and Medicare, Domenici said. 
</P>
<P>
	He accused President Clinton, who has threatened to veto the tax  
cuts, of wanting ``to keep all the money in Washington and give 
none back to overtaxed American families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House says the bill's benefits are skewed toward  
wealthier people, would do little to protect Social Security and 
Medicare and could require deep cuts in critical spending programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a decade, the bill would reduce all income tax rates by one  
percentage point, cut capital gains taxes, improve retirement 
savings, ease the ``marriage penalty'' paid by many two-income 
couples, gradually eliminate the alternative minimum tax, provide 
new breaks for education and health care and benefit large and 
small businesses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:48:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ayala Makes Comeback From Jail Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tony Ayala Jr. tried to keep his comeback win  
in perspective, even as hometown fans continued to chant his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen years in prison evidently taught him something.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, some years ago I made a terrible mistake,'' Ayala  
said. ``No fight will be able to replace that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Ayala didn't want the rape that sent him to prison for  
nearly half his life lost in the excitement of his third round 
knockout Friday night of Manuel Esparaza, the crowd of 10,676 that 
packed the Freeman Coliseum was in a more forgiving mood. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the fight, two middle-aged women carried a large banner  
around the ring that read ``Hispanic women for better justice 
support Torito.'' Other fans waved cards reading ``Torito, heeee's 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For one night, at least, it seemed like he was, though it was  
against an opponent who would never have been considered for the 
fighter dubbed El Torito in his prime. 
</P>
<P>
	``The passion was still there,'' Ayala said after knocking  
Esparaza down twice in the third round -- the first time with a 
vicious left hook to the ribs. ``I think things turned out real 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala's first rounds in the ring since he scored a third round  
knockout of Carlos Herrera on Nov. 20, 1982, earned him both the 
adulation of the hometown fans and a $200,000 purse. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't a stylistic fight, but for a boxer who hadn't fought  
in nearly 17 years, it wasn't a bad performance at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt like the old days,'' Ayala said. ``My power felt good.  
My timing was a bit off and I'll have to work on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The win over the skinny 21-year-old Esparaza -- who qualified for  
the fight after being knocked out in the sixth round of his last 
fight -- was more notable in that it showed that Ayala hadn't lost 
the punch that made him such a ferocious fighter in his heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala was signed to fight Davey Moore for the junior  
middleweight championship when, on New Year's Day 1983, he entered 
a woman's residence and brutally raped her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've grown up and paid for my mistakes,'' said Ayala, released  
in April after serving 16 years of a 35-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala's father, Tony Ayala Sr., was in his son's corner just as  
he had been in his career as a teen-age sensation, and was happy 
with both the reception given his son and the outcome of the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had to grade him, I'd give him a B-plus,'' the father  
said. ``He's not going to box like he used to. He's going to be 
slipping and boxing more. He could have gone 12 rounds tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now that Ayala is fighting again, he's in a hurry to make up for  
lost time. 
</P>
<P>
	Another fight is in the works for September, and Ayala is  
already talking about returning to the level where he can fight for 
a middleweight or junior middleweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not 19 anymore and I can't go into a fight punching with a  
lack of abandon,'' Ayala said. ``But I hope that within a year I'll 
be better than anyone in the world.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
