<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged To Send Cash to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American officials have two words of advice  
for Americans eager to help earthquake victims in Turkey: Send 
cash. 
</P>
<P>
	They do not want to repeat last fall's experience with Hurricane  
Mitch in Central America when many material items sent by Americans 
just got in the way or were inappropriate, such as winter coats. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying hard to discourage people from sending things,''  
Harriet Babbitt, the No. 2 official at the U.S. Agency for 
International Development, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	AID is urging Americans to call 800-872-4373 (USAID-RELIEF)  
during normal business hours if they wish to make a cash donation 
through one of the more than two dozen private voluntary agencies 
involved in the relief effort. Donors can also call InterAction, an 
umbrella group for private voluntary organizations at 202-667-8227. 
</P>
<P>
	During natural disasters such as Hurricane Mitch, ``piles of  
goods get in the way of legitimate goods coming in,'' said Bryna 
Brennan, head of public affairs at the Pan American Health 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bad goods keep out good goods,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Turkish authorities are welcoming donations of certain kinds of  
material goods. A list of more than 100 items considered ``urgently 
required'' ranges from tents and body bags to jackhammers and 
surgical kits. The great majority of the items are medicines and 
medical equipment. The complete list is carried on InterAction's 
Web site: www.interaction.org. 
</P>
<P>
	Individuals or institutions wishing to make donations can  
contact the Turkish Red Crescent in Istanbul at 90-212-227 51 64 or 
90-212-227 51 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish Airlines will transport donated material to Istanbul  
free of charge on its flights from New York, Chicago and Miami. 
Routine customs requirements have been waived. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistance from across ethnic and religious lines has been made  
available in response to the grim pictures of death and devastation 
in western Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Jewish Committee said Friday it is making a cash  
donation of $225,000 to predominantly Muslim Turkey. Earlier, the 
AJC contributed $25,000. Perhaps facilitating the AJC generosity 
are the friendly ties Israel maintains with Turkey. But Greece and 
Greek Cypriots also have made contributions to the relief effort 
despite their long-standing enmity toward Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt said AID contributions to earthquake relief total about  
$3 million and are increasing. The Pentagon also has contributed to 
the assistance effort, but no figures were available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
