<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Bret Gains Momentum  
</P>
<P>
	MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) -- The first Atlantic hurricane this year  
gathered strength Saturday and churned through the Gulf of Mexico 
towards the Texas-Mexico border with 135-mph winds. Forecasters 
upgraded Hurricane Bret to a Class 4 hurricane and said it could 
strengthen further before making an expected landfall sometime 
Sunday near Brownsville, Texas, and Matamoros, Mexico, twin cities 
on the border. Hurricanes are categorized in five classes, the 
fifth being the strongest. 

</P>
<P>
	Bomb Kills 17 in Algeria  
</P>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- A bomb exploded at a party south of the  
capital, killing 17 people, including two children, and wounding 12 
others, security officials said Saturday. The bomb was thrown into 
the middle of a celebration late Friday in the small town of 
Ouzera, 60 miles south of the coastal capital, Algiers, officials 
said. Authorities have blamed recurring violence on Islamic 
insurgents, who have been fighting to topple the government of the 
northern Africa country since 1992. That was the year the 
military-backed government canceled elections that the Islamic 
Salvation Front was set to win. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Finding Fewer Earthquake Survivors  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- With just six people rescued Saturday  
and some 30,000 others presumed to be trapped beneath the rubble of 
buildings ruined by Turkey's massive earthquake, hopes dimmed that 
more survivors will be found. Experts say people trapped in such 
situations usually can survive only 72 hours because of 
dehydration, or until early Friday in this case. Authorities 
refocused their efforts on preventing disease and finding shelter 
for hundreds of thousands of people left homeless by Turkey's 
massive quake. Many of the homes that collapsed were constructed 
with substandard materials, provoking public outrage at builders. 

</P>
<P>
	Giant Panda Gives Birth at San Diego Zoo  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- One of only three giant pandas in the United  
States gave birth to a cub Saturday at the San Diego Zoo. Bai Yun, 
a 213-pound giant panda on loan from China, delivered the cub at 
11:40 a.m. in a specially constructed den at the San Diego Zoo. It 
was the first baby panda born in the western hemisphere since 1990, 
zoo officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Farms in East Ravaged by Drought  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- Five entire states -- Kentucky, West  
Virginia, Delaware, Massachusetts and South Carolina -- have been 
declared disaster areas by the Department of Agriculture because of 
drought. Livestock auctions are booming throughout the 
drought-stricken East, as farmers are forced to sell animals they 
can no longer feed. Many farmers also are faced with grain, 
vegetable and tobacco crops that have been ravaged by dry weather. 
Supermarket shoppers, however, will hardly notice, especially at 
major chains that buy produce on a national market, USDA Chief 
Economist Keith Collins said Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	Effort To Oust Milosevic Set Back  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a setback to efforts to unseat  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the head of the Serbian 
Renewal Movement accused another opposition group of pushing the 
country to civil war by refusing offers of early elections to end 
the political crisis that followed the 78-day NATO bombing 
campaign. Vuk Draskovic wants to accept the Milosevic government's 
offer of early elections this fall. Zoran Djindjic and his allies, 
by contrast, insist that Milosevic step down immediately and make 
way for a transitional government pending new elections under 
international supervision. 

</P>
<P>
	Twins Beat Yankees 6-1  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Eric Milton allowed one run in 7 1-3 innings,  
baffling his former team for the second time this week, as the 
Minnesota Twins beat the New York Yankees 6-1 Saturday night to 
snap a five-game losing streak. Milton (5-10), traded from New York 
to Minnesota on Feb. 6, 1998 for Chuck Knoblauch, allowed six hits 
while striking out six and walking one. Roger Clemens (11-6) 
allowed five runs and nine hits in 6 2-3 innings as New York lost 
for the third time in four games. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Billionaire Interested in Jets  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- According to two NFL owners, Kirk Kerkorian, the  
owner of the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas, has expressed an 
interest in buying the New York Jets, The New York Times reported 
Sunday. One owner, who was not identified by the Times, said the 
chances for Kerkorian, 82, to successfully buy the team are ``good 
if he really wants them.'' Potential owners can make a bid and 
those bids will be presented to the estate of former owner Leon 
Hess, which will accept the highest or most agreeable offer. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
