<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 09:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crewman Killed in Auto Race Mishap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELMA, Wash. (AP) -- One man was killed and two others were  
injured when a sprint car crashed in the pit area during pre-race 
preparations at Grays Harbor Raceway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly W. Pole, 37, of Canada, was pronounced dead on arrival  
Friday night at Mark Reed Hospital in McCleary, Grays Harbor County 
undersheriff Rich Scott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another crewman -- 65-year-old Charles Dunlap of Olympia --  
suffered a broken leg. He was in stable condition this morning and 
was expected to undergo surgery at Providence St. Peter Hospital in 
Olympia. 
</P>
<P>
	A third pit crewman, 26-year-old Walter Bachman of Kent, was  
treated at Mark Reed Hospital and released Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened as pit crews were preparing a record field  
of 52 sprint cars for racing and several cars were ``packing the 
track,'' driving around at low speeds to smooth the track's clay 
surface. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 81D car developed throttle problems and a crewman who  
was driving headed for the pits to fix the problem, sheriff's Lt. 
Matt Stowers said. To reach the pits, a driver must turn left 
sharply and proceed down a long aisle filled with pit crews and 
support vehicles on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The alcohol-fueled engine revved abnormally high and the car  
began to spin, Stowers said. The car clipped another car, spun 
across the aisle and plowed into the No. 4 car, fatally injuring 
Pole, then plowed into the No. 21 car, injuring the two other men. 
</P>
<P>
	The sheriff's office was investigating.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
