<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 06:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Games Athlete Has Leg Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Egyptian squash player Nesreene Nasha't  
underwent surgery Saturday to repair a bone in her left leg that 
was broken in a bus accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasha't, who also suffered a concussion, was in satisfactory  
condition, according to officials at the King Hussein Medical City 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasha't underwent two operations Friday to fix a fractured jaw  
and a broken thigh bone. 
</P>
<P>
	Her colleagues were at her bedside in the Intensive Care Unit  
after she woke up from surgery Saturday, one of the hospital 
officials said on customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a bus carrying several Egyptian athletes overturned,  
killing the Jordanian driver, whose name was not disclosed. Members 
of the Egyptian squash team were on an outing to the city of Madaba 
on their day off between matches they are playing at the Arab Games 
in Amman. 
</P>
<P>
	Four other team members, including Iman Amir and Umniya Abdul  
Qawi, sustained bruises. They were reportedly in stable condition 
at the same hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Amir won the silver medal and Qawi the bronze in the women's  
squash championship Thursday. Nasha't finished eighth in the 
individual championship, which ended Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear whether the Egyptian team was intending to  
carry on with the team competitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan's state-run Petra news agency said King Abdullah II  
visited the Egyptians at the hospital earlier Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's accident occurred outside Madaba, 20 miles southwest of  
Amman. The city is known for its Byzantine ruins. It is also the 
site of Mount Nebo, where Moses is said to have sighted the 
promised land. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
