<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Slain in South Africa Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KWAMASHU, South Africa (AP) -- Gunmen shot and killed nine  
people, including three children, and burned houses in this black 
township, police said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims, who also included four men and two women, lived in  
three homes near each other in the township of KwaMashu. The gunmen 
burned down two of the houses, said Director Bala Naidoo, police 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The shootings started late Friday night and ended four hours  
later before dawn Saturday, Naidoo said. The spokesman did not give 
the ages of the slain children. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional police and army units were called into the area on  
Saturday, and leaders from the African National Congress and the 
Inkatha Freedom Party visited the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian Ocean province of KwaZulu-Natal has seen much  
political violence since the mid 1980s, but the area of KwaMashu -- 
around 18 miles north of the port city of Durban -- has been quiet 
in recent years, Naidoo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mtholephi Mthimkhulu, a provincial legislator from the ANC, said  
the motive for the killing did not appear to be political, the 
South African Press Association reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mthimkhulu said one of the victims had been accused earlier in  
the week of harboring criminals at his house, and another of the 
victims had defended him at a public meeting. The police 
investigator, Bongani Ntanjana, said he could not confirm the 
allegation, Sapa reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A reward of up to $41,000 has been offered by police -- an  
unusual step that was used in this violence prone province once 
before this year, Naidoo said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a different case, police said Saturday they have arrested a  
sixth suspect in the January slaying of controversial opposition 
politician Sifiso Nkabinde in Richmond, about 60 miles northwest of 
Durban. Five other suspects were arrested over the past week for 
the killing, which set off revenge massacres. 
</P>
<P>
	Police did not release the name of the sixth suspect, arrested  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the suspects had close ties to Richmond mayor Andrew  
Ragavaloo, a member of the ruling African National Congress. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
