<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Panda Cubs Born; 1 Dies in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A giant panda gave birth to a rare three-cub  
litter this week in southwest China's Sichuan province, but the 
smallest of the three cubs has died, the state-run Xinhua News 
Agency reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The cub, which was born Wednesday at the Giant Panda Breeding  
Research Center, died of a bladder disorder. It had been deserted 
by its mother when a caretaker found it, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two cubs were healthy, the report said.  
</P>
<P>
	Giant pandas, an endangered species, usually give birth to only  
one or two cubs. A litter of three is rare. The animals are not 
prolific breeders, and the survival rate for cubs is low. 
</P>
<P>
	The giant panda is native only to China. Loss of its natural  
habitat and poaching threaten to cause its extinction. Only about 
1,000 survive in captivity and in the wild. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
