<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 15:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two-Time Champ Flops in Shot Put </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- John Godina let his shot put world title  
slip away Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Plagued by trouble with his footing, the two-time World  
Championships gold medalist fouled on five of six attempts during 
the final, settling for seventh place behind fellow American C.J. 
Hunter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to say my head is spinning right now,'' Godina said.  
``It's hard to tell what my problem was today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 Olympic silver medalist, who led the field in the  
morning qualifying session, connected on just one effort -- his 
second -- in the final. That traveled 66 feet, 9 1/4 inches. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old appeared to be out of sorts, talking to himself  
and shaking his head between turns in the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	On his final attempt, Godina started to spin, the shot tucked  
under his chin, but came to a sudden halt -- a rare sight in the 
event -- and asked that the ring be swept. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite being given a chance to start the attempt over,  
Godina produced a foul. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a muted end to a disappointing showing from the man who  
owns the world's leading throw this year, a career-best 72-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows John's the best and John just had a bad night.  
If I had to guess, it looked like he was rushing things a little 
bit,'' said Andy Bloom of the United States, who was fourth 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter claimed his first major international title by eclipsing  
his career best with a final effort of 71-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figured (Hunter) would step up. Somebody had to,'' Godina  
said, a blank look on his face. ``It sure wasn't me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Oliver-Sven Buder took his second straight worlds  
silver in the shot with 70-3 1/2, while world indoor champion 
Alexander Bagach of Ukraine was third in 69-9. 
</P>
<P>
	Godina picked up his gold at the 1997 worlds with a little help.  
He was fourth at the U.S. Championships, not good enough to qualify 
for the worlds, but the International Amateur Athletic Federation 
decided to invite 1995 world champions to defend their titles as 
wild-card entries. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, during the competition, Godina finished second behind  
Bagach. But Bagach tested positive for the stimulant ephedrine and 
was stripped of his gold medal and the $60,000 first prize -- 
leaving both for Godina. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 285-pound Godina gets another shot at a medal here  
in the discus competition. Qualifying is Sunday, the final Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Godina was fifth in the discus at the 1997 worlds, and 10th in  
the event four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really upset for John, I know how hard he works,'' Hunter  
said. ``But this may make him come back even stronger.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:53:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Orders Serbs To Hand In Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO ordered Serbs in a southern  
Kosovo town to hand in their weapons Saturday or face arrest in a 
last-minute crackdown before Dutch troops turn security over to the 
Russians. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Kosovo capital, Pristina, a joint Serb-ethnic Albanian  
council formed to advise the U.N. mission held its second meeting 
Saturday -- but without Kosovo Liberation Army leader Hashim Thaci. 
</P>
<P>
	Thaci's rival, moderate politician Ibrahim Rugova, boycotted the  
first session July 16, complaining about the allocation of seats. 
Rugova, elected president of the unrecognized Republic of Kosovo, 
was present at Saturday's meeting, along with U.N. and NATO 
representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Thaci and Rugova claim leadership of Kosovo's majority  
ethnic Albanian community. Chief U.N. administrator Bernard 
Kouchner said Thaci told him earlier he would be out of the country 
but would attend the next meeting, scheduled for Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Early Saturday, German and Dutch troops posted signs throughout  
a Serb neighborhood in the city of Orahovac with the names of Serbs 
NATO believes were given weapons by Serb police. 
</P>
<P>
	The signs ordered Serbs to turn in their weapons Saturday to  
NATO collection points in the center of town. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you respond to this, you will be freed of punishment,'' the  
signs said. The warning added that peacekeepers would begin 
house-to-house searches after the deadline, and ``if we find any 
weapons, you will be arrested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-afternoon Saturday, NATO officials said Serbs had turned  
in 120 weapons, mostly Kalashnikov rifles. 
</P>
<P>
	Orahovac, 40 miles southwest of Pristina, is in the  
German-controlled sector of Kosovo. Dutch soldiers have been 
stationed there for weeks but are to hand the town over to Russian 
peacekeepers starting Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians resent the Russians, accusing them of favoring  
their fellow Slavic Serbs. Many Serbs believe only the Russians can 
protect them from ethnic Albanians seeking revenge after an 
18-month crackdown in Kosovo, a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's 
dominant republic. Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic withdrew 
Serbian forces from the province as part of a peace plan reached in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, NATO said Dutch and German peacekeepers arrested  
three Kosovo Serbs in Orahovac on suspicion of committing 
atrocities against ethnic Albanians during the crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency said four people were  
detained in Orahovac and described them as ``respected figures'' in 
the community. 
</P>
<P>
	In a commentary Saturday, Tanjug denounced the arrests, calling  
them a ``grotesque move'' and claiming NATO troops ``have turned 
the barrels of their guns on the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Reprisal attacks have prompted most of Kosovo's former  
200,000-member Serb community to seek sanctuary in other parts of 
Yugoslavia. The majority of the province's population is ethnic 
Albanian. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, two Serb brothers were wounded when ethnic  
Albanians attacked Banje village in central Kosovo, Tanjug 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	French troops rushed to the scene and transported the two to the  
nearby French military hospital, Tanjug said. The agency said 
villagers demanded a meeting with French officers and threatened to 
leave the province if they could not be protected. 
</P>
<P>
	Four Serbs were wounded Friday night when ethnic Albanians  
hurled grenades from a car in a village west of Pristina, the 
private Yugoslav news agency FoNet said. The wounded were evacuated 
by Russian troops. Other Serb villagers barricaded the road, 
demanding international protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian government has complained about NATO's failure to  
protect Serbs and warned that Moscow might withdraw its troops from 
Kosovo or change their role there if conditions become 
``unacceptable.'' It did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with NATO's inability to stop the attacks, Momcilo  
Trajkovic, a Serb community leader, suggested Saturday that 
peacekeepers establish all-Serb enclaves in areas of Kosovo where 
Serbs were in the majority before the Western bombing campaign 
against Yugoslavia began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Kouchner promised to study the proposal and present a written  
response Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO hopes that attacks will ease as the KLA gradually disarms  
under an agreement signed in June. The deal calls for final 
disarmament by Sept. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest deadline was midnight Friday, when the KLA was to  
have surrendered 60 percent of its weapons. KLA military commander 
Gen. Agim Ceku claims the group met the deadline a day in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials said they want to inventory the weapons before  
confirming the claim. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:56:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Silverbulletday Wins Alabama Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- The beaten-favorite jinx in the  
Alabama Stakes was trampled Saturday under the flying hooves of 
Silverbulletday at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4-5 betting choice simply ran away from six rivals as she  
became the first favorite to win the Grade I stakes for 3-year-old 
fillies since Sky Beauty in 1993. Four of the beaten favorites in 
the five previous runnings of the Alabama were odds-on. The other 
was even money. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth or fourth until a half-mile remained, Silverbulletday then  
was moved into third by Jerry Bailey. She was second and pressuring 
Strolling Belle approaching the quarter pole. 
</P>
<P>
	Then -- whoosh! -- Silverbulletday was gone, and the end of the 1 1/4  
miles she was 9 lengths ahead Strolling Belle. Gandria was another 
3 lengths back and 6 1/2 lengths ahead of On a Soapbox. 
</P>
<P>
	``Awesome -- that's the word that says it best,'' Bailey said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really impressed with her performance,'' owner Mike Pegram  
said. ``She's a gift from heaven and a once-in-a-lifetime horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday finished in 2:02 3-5 under level weight of 121  
pounds after a final quarter in under 24 seconds. Although it had 
rained for most of the afternoon, the track was listed as fast and 
the rain virtually had stopped by the 4:45 p.m. post time for the 
Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the seventh win in eight starts and 13th in 15 career  
outings for Silverbulletday, trained by Bob Baffert. It also was 
her 10th straight win over fillies and her first at beyond 1 1/8 
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	There was speculation that 1 1/4 miles might be too far for  
Silverbulletday after her seventh-place finish in the 1 1/2-mile 
Belmont Stakes on June 5. The Belmont, however, was against colts. 
Against fillies, she simply is in a league of her own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to keep her with the fillies,'' Baffert said. ``I  
think it's one of those things where we're enjoying her. With Real 
Quiet being out, you have to enjoy the moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert trains and Pegram owns Real Quiet, the 1998 Kentucky  
Derby and Preakness winner and winner of the Pimlico Special and 
Hollywood Gold Cup this year. Real Quiet cracked a bone in his 
right front leg last Sunday and is finished for the year -- maybe 
for good. 
</P>
<P>
	Pegram indicated Silverbulletday would next start in the Grade I  
Spinster on Oct. 16 at Keeneland, where she could face Banshee 
Breeze, the 1998 champion 3-year-old filly, who is unbeaten in four 
starts this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday paid $2.80, $2.50 and $2.10 and earned $240,000  
from a purse of $400,000, boosting her earnings to $2,601,750. 
</P>
<P>
	Strolling Belle, ridden by Mike Smith, returned $6.50 and $2.10.  
Canadian-bred Gandria, ridden by Shane Sellers, paid $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing the order of finish after On a Soapbox were Adam's  
Time, Back in Shape and Brushed Halory. 
</P>
<P>
	On a Soapbox, ridden by Robby Albarado, had won the 1 1/2-mile  
Coaching Club American Oaks on July 24 at Belmont Park, but she was 
never in contention Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:56:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
