<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Death Toll Tops 11,000  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- As the death toll passed 11,000, rescue  
workers fearing the spread of disease began setting up tent cities 
and organizing food distribution today for the tens of thousands 
left homeless by Turkey's massive quake. The toll is expected to 
keep rising as crews tackle mountains of rubble where possibly tens 
of thousands of bodies are buried. Five people were rescued today, 
including a 95-year-old woman. But for each miracle survivor, 
hundreds more corpses are recovered. Officials worried about 
outbreaks of typhoid fever, cholera or dysentery sprayed 
disinfectants and distributed water purification tablets in 
hard-hit areas. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Cuts Ex-Spy Director's Clearance  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a highly unusual move, the CIA pulled the  
security clearances for former Director John Deutch, unwilling to 
excuse his violation of agency rules by keeping secret files on an 
unsecured home computer. A CIA spokesman said yesterday he knew of 
no precedent for the action taken against Deutch, a former deputy 
defense secretary who spent 38 years in public service before 
leaving the CIA in December 1996. The decision to suspend Deutch's 
security clearances was made by CIA Director George Tenet, Deutch's 
successor. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Army Cop Allegedly Kills Boss  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A U.S. military policeman shot and  
killed his superior early today at a base near the North Korean 
border and was arrested eight hours later, the U.S. Military 
Command said. South Korean Police said they believe Jacob M. 
Bowley, a private from the 55th Military Police Company at Camp Red 
Cloud, north of Seoul, was drunk at the time. Bowley was angry with 
the sergeant because she ordered a blood test on one of his friends 
to determine whether he consumed alcohol while he was off the base 
without permission, said South Korea's national news agency. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Claims 100 Rebels Killed  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russia's military command said today  
that its forces have killed up to 100 Muslim rebels in a single day 
of fighting in the southern area of Dagestan, but President Boris 
Yeltsin's spokesman warned radio listeners that it is ``impossible 
to expect a quick solution'' to the uprising. Meanwhile, Russian 
troops managed to capture strategic heights near two villages in 
Dagestan earlier seized by the guerrillas. Air raids continued 
through the day today, and some woods in the area were on fire, the 
Interior Ministry said. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysian Opposition Leader Cleared  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- An opposition leader accused of  
criticizing Malaysia's judicial system was cleared of contempt 
charges today after the prosecution failed to prove he made the 
critical comments, which were published on the Internet. High Court 
Judge Ariffin Jaka dismissed the contempt charge against Chandra 
Muzaffar. Chandra is the deputy president of the opposition 
National Justice Party and a close ally of ousted deputy prime 
minister Anwar Ibrahim. Defense attorneys argued that the contempt 
action was flawed because prosecutors were relying on material from 
the Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Sale of Hitler Book Stopped  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- German media giant Bertelsmann has stopped selling  
Adolf Hitler's ``Mein Kampf'' in its online bookstore, a spokesman 
said today. BOL International's German services never offered the 
book, but its British and French services did, company spokesman 
Christof Ehrhart said. He said those sales were ended this week to 
block Germans from buying the book. Under German law, books 
espousing Nazi philosophy are banned from display or sale. 
Bertelsmann has asked its U.S.-based Internet partner, 
barnesandnoble.com, not to ship banned Nazi titles to customers in 
Germany. 

</P>
<P>
	Land Mine Hurts Elephant in Myanmar  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai veterinarians may have to amputate  
an elephant's leg up to the knee and fit the animal with a 
prosthesis after he stepped on a land mine in the jungles of 
neighboring Myanmar. The 38-year-old pachyderm, named Motola, 
walked on a land mine as he was foraging for food on the rugged 
Thai-Myanmar border during a break from hauling logs. Vets are 
administering jumbo-size doses of painkillers. They also plan to 
hoist up the three-ton elephant with a crane or pulley to take the 
weight off his foot. 

</P>
<P>
	Jones Advances in 100, Long Jump  
</P>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Marion Jones launched her bid for an  
unprecedented four gold medals and Maurice Greene opened his quest 
for a rare sprint double at the World Championships today, easily 
winning their first-round heats in the 100-meter dash. Jones also 
advanced to the final of the long jump. Jones, who is seeking gold 
medals in the 100, 200, long jump and relay, will run her 
second-round heat in the 100 later in the day. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
