<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pawtucket's Martinez Feels No Pain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) -- Ramon Martinez allowed six runs and six  
hits, including three home runs, in five innings in a 
rehabilitation start for the Triple-A Pawtucket Red Sox on Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news for Martinez was that he retired seven of the last  
eight batters he faced and felt no pain in his surgically-repaired 
right shoulder against the Buffalo Bisons. Buffalo won 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Los Angeles Dodger standout said he was nonetheless  
encouraged with his first start above the Single-A level in 14 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel fine. I'm making a lot of progress,'' said Martinez,  
who underwent rotator cuff surgery on his right shoulder in June 
1998 while with the Dodgers and has not pitched in the major 
leagues since. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way I feel is a good thing. My location wasn't real  
consistent, but the last couple innings it was much better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, 2-0 with a 2.00 ERA in eight rehab starts at Class-A,  
threw 77 pitches, 46 for strikes. He struck out three and walked 
two. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez had an easy first inning, walking one batter. But the  
31-year-old right-hander gave up six runs and five hits in the 
second and third innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``My location was off in the those middle two innings,''  
Martinez said. ``That's the way it always was for me in the big 
leagues. It always takes me a while to get focused in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez finished strongly, retiring seven of the last eight  
batters he faced. He escaped the third inning with a groundout, 
pitched a 1-2-3 fourth inning and gave up an infield single to lead 
off the sixth inning before retiring the side on two strikeouts and 
a groundout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was off in those two middle innings, but I found my location  
in the last couple innings and that's what I'm going to take away 
from this game,'' said Martinez, 123-77 with 3.45 ERA in 11 seasons 
with Los Angeles before signing with Boston in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez's velocity in his struggling second and third innings  
topped out at 86 miles per hour, according to scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'll ever throw 95 again like I could,''  
Martinez said. ``Maybe I can get up to 90 or 92. But you don't have 
to throw 95 to pitch in the big leagues, you have to have 
location.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston has been hoping to have Martinez join his younger  
brother, Pedro, on the Red Sox's roster for the stretch run of the 
regular season. Martinez said the goal remains very much in sight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I need one more start down here and then I'll be  
ready,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
