<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Turkey's Dead Could Rise to 40,000  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The official death toll from Turkey's  
earthquake stands at more than 12,000, but a member of the U.N. 
Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs said it could 
possibly rise as high as 40,000. As hopes dim that more survivors 
will be found, authorities refocused their efforts on providing 
shelter for hundreds of thousands of people left homeless. Most of 
the 30,000 still missing are presumed to be trapped beneath rubble. 
Experts say people in such situations usually can survive only 72 
hours because of dehydration, or early yesterday in this case. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Headed Toward Texas  
</P>
<P>
	BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- People were given until sunup tomorrow  
to get off South Padre Island as Hurricane Bret took aim at the 
southern tip of Texas and neighboring Mexico. Coastal residents 
today stocked up at gasoline pumps and grocery stores, and building 
supply stores were overrun with customers wanting plywood, nails, 
flashlights and generators. Officials of popular South Padre Island 
ordered all 2,100 residents to pack and leave by 6 a.m. tomorrow. 
By this afternoon, Bret was located about 210 miles southeast of 
Brownsville. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Feds Raid Bank of New York  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Federal investigators reportedly raided the Wall  
Street office of the Bank of New York in connection to a major 
international money-laundering scheme that authorities say involves 
the Russian mob. During Friday's raid, investigators seized the 
files of Natasha Gurfinkel Kagalovsky, a senior vice president who 
supervised the bank's East European division, a source close to the 
bank told The New York Times in today's editions. As much as $10 
billion allegedly was laundered through the bank in what 
investigators say is an operation run by Russian organized crime, 
the Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Opposition Showing Cracks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Efforts to unseat Slobodan Milosevic  
were set back when an opposition leader denounced rivals in the 
movement and said his followers would boycott joint rallies aimed 
at forcing the Yugoslav president to step down. Vuk Draskovic, head 
of the Serbian Renewal Movement, accused another opposition group 
led by Zoran Djindjic of pushing the country to civil war by 
refusing offers of early elections to end the political crisis that 
followed the 78-day NATO bombing campaign. Draskovic wants to 
accept the Milosevic government's offer of early elections this 
fall. Djindjic insists that Milosevic step down immediately and 
make way for a transitional government. 

</P>
<P>
	Domenici Says Citizens Have Overpaid  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republicans' $792 billion package of tax  
cuts is the party's way of refunding money that citizens have 
overpaid, Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici said 
today. A projected surplus over the next decade would leave $1.5 
trillion to give back to taxpayers, even after most of the money is 
reserved to strengthen Social Security and Medicare, the New 
Mexican Republican said in the party's weekly radio address. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwandan Troops Control Congo Town  
</P>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Congo's third-largest town is now  
controlled by Rwandan troops who clashed with their Ugandan allies 
early this week, a Ugandan newspaper reported today. The 
government-owned New Vision newspaper said most of Kisangani was 
under Rwandan control except for the largest hotel, the Palm Beach. 
Rwanda says it has supported Congolese rebels to help root out 
Rwandan Hutu extremists fighting alongside Congolese President 
Laurent Kabila and who helped carry out the genocide of at least 
500,000 Tutsis and politically moderate Hutus in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
	Younger Japanese Seek New Paths  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A growing number of young people in Japan are  
trading the security of doing things by the book -- no questions 
asked -- for a much riskier venture: playing by their own rules. 
Teens are taking time out from nonstop studying to volunteer with 
the elderly or handicapped. Twentysomethings are giving up the 
safety of established corporations for the freedom of founding new 
companies. Studies say that even those taking the accepted path to 
success are putting more emphasis on getting jobs in fields they 
are interested in, despite less pay and prestige. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Top Rockies With 2 Sosa Homers  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa hit his major-league leading 50th and  
51st home runs today for his second two-homer game in as many days 
to lead the Chicago Cubs to an 8-6 victory over the Colorado 
Rockies. Sosa became the fourth player ever to post consecutive 
50-homer seasons, joining Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Babe 
Ruth. And for the second straight year, Sosa hit Nos. 50 and 51 on 
the same day -- only this year it came after 121 games, nine games 
earlier than in 1998. Sosa now leads Mark McGwire by three home 
runs. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  








  	   	
</P>
