<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Billionaire May Buy Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- According to two NFL owners, Kirk Kerkorian, the  
owner of the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas, has expressed an 
interest in buying the New York Jets, The New York Times reported 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	One owner, who was not identified by the Times, said the chances  
for Kerkorian, 82, to successfully buy the team are ``good if he 
really wants them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Potential owners can make a bid and those bids will be presented  
to the estate of former owner Leon Hess, which will accept the 
highest or most agreeable offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, in his will, barred any member of his family from  
participating in the team's future, ``either directly or 
indirectly, in any capacity whatsoever.'' Hess died in May at age 
85. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess' estate hired the investment firm Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Company  
to handle the sale. Financial experts have said that the Jets could 
be sold for $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerkorian is one of the richest men in the world, according to  
Forbes Magazine, with an estimated net worth of $3.8 billion. He 
built the Trans International Airline charter service following 
World War II and sold it in 1968 for $104 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He is expected to receive a prospectus book from Goldman, Sachs.  
</P>
<P>
	Other potential bidders for the team are real estate developer  
Samuel J. LeFrak, New York Mets co-owner Nelson Doubleday, New 
Jersey Devils owner John McMullen and Cablevision chairman Charles 
Dolan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
