<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Landmark D.C. Cafeteria Survives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's capital is fickle when it comes to  
tradition. But one longtime Washington monument to a bygone era of 
cheap and tasty food has survived its near expiration with the help 
of supporters who included members of Congress and the homeless. 
</P>
<P>
	Sholl's Colonial Cafeteria, a stalwart server of home-style  
cooking since 1928, has renewed its once-endangered lease at almost 
$30,000 less per year than the landlord wanted, averting financial 
straits that would have put the restaurant under. 
</P>
<P>
	The new lease was signed this week by proprietor George  
Fleishell, who serves up liver and onions, roast beef, soups, 
salads, vegetables, lemonade and nine kinds of pie. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourist buses regularly line up outside the entrance of Sholl's,  
downtown near the end of the K Street corridor that houses many of 
the city's lobbyists and lawyers, including some who are Sholl's 
regulars. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., is also a loyal patron, and Sholl's has  
counted Harry S. Truman, George Wallace and Jimmy Carter among its 
customers. Sholl's also works with several homeless advocates and 
honors their meal vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	When Fleishell announced earlier this year that the rent  
increase would drive Sholl's out of business, its patrons launched 
a ``Save Our Sholl's Committee'' that garnered the national 
publicity that apparently made the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleishell, the 71-year-old nephew of founder Evan Sholl, said  
Friday he had agreed to pay rent of $255,000 per year, up from 
$235,000 but less than the $282,000 the landlord wanted. (The 
landlord's identity is a bit of a mystery, and Fleishell dealt with 
rental agent Cushman &AMP; Wakefield.) 
</P>
<P>
	``They finally came around,'' Fleishell said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
