<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Bret Nears Tex-Mex Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) -- The first Atlantic hurricane this year  
gathered strength Saturday and churned through the Gulf of Mexico 
towards the Texas-Mexico border with 135-mph winds. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters upgraded Hurricane Bret to a Class 4 hurricane and  
said it could strengthen further before making an expected landfall 
sometime Sunday near Brownsville, Texas and Matamoros, Mexico, twin 
cities on the border. Hurricanes are categorized in five classes, 
the fifth being the strongest. 
</P>
<P>
	``People should already be making preparations,'' said Roberto  
Molleda, a meteorologist with the U.S. National Hurricane Center in 
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 p.m. EDT, Hurricane Bret was located about 155 miles  
southeast of Brownsville, Texas, moving north at about 10 mph, but 
the center said that pace could slacken as the storm takes a turn 
to the northwest over the next 6 to 12 hours, the center reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our forecast has the center of the eye of the hurricane coming  
ashore right at the Texas-Mexico border'' sometime Sunday afternoon 
or evening, Molleda said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane warnings were extended to cover an approximately  
200-mile stretch of the Texas coast from the border to Port 
O'Connor. A hurricane watch covers another 75 miles north along the 
coast to Freeport. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mexico, the warnings were in effect for a 160-mile stretch of  
Mexico's northern Gulf coast from Matamoros south to La Pesca. The 
watch extended another 200 miles south to Tuxpan. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Matamoros, a city of 360,000 across the border from  
Brownsville, rushed to tape up windows to keep them from being 
blown out by the storm. Sandbags were piled waist-high in front of 
a local Burger King restaurant, and stores were packed with 
residents buying food and drinking water. 
</P>
<P>
	Matamoros Mayor Homero Zamora Ayala declared a state of alert  
for the city's 360,000 residents, and told local media that as many 
as 7,000 people would be evacuated from low-lying coastal areas 
there. City Attorney General Juan Martin Reina said 22 city buses 
had already been sent to bring 500 people from beach communities to 
an improvised shelter at a convention center. 
</P>
<P>
	``These communities are near the Gulf shore ... their houses are  
made of wood and could easily be flooded,'' Reina said. Gray clouds 
already lowered ominously over the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Leticia Jimenez, 39, stood in front of a food store on the  
outskirts of Matamoros with a shopping cart loaded with bottled 
water, batteries and canned food, and recalled Hurricane Gilbert, 
which devastated the area in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``This time we're taking more time to get prepared,'' Jimenez  
said, as last-minute shoppers jammed the store's parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	The hurricane could cause storm surges and coastal flooding 8 to  
12 feet above normal tides. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Bret could be the first major hurricane to hit the  
area since Gilbert in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	As it took aim at Texas' lower coast, officials of South Padre  
Island -- a popular resort island in the Gulf of Mexico -- ordered 
the 2,100 residents to pack and leave by sunup Sunday, Mayor Ed 
Cyganiewicz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Port Isabel, on the mainland side of the causeway  
to the low-lying barrier island, were told to evacuate by morning. 
School buses were being deployed to transport residents to inland 
shelters, Cameron County Judge Gilberto Hinojosa said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	If residents don't want to leave, Hinojosa said, ``then we hand  
out little body tags.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not going to live if you stay on the island and the  
hurricane hits,'' he said. ``You're going to drown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Previous hurricane warnings for the Mexican Gulf coast further  
south in the coastal state of Tamaulipas were downgraded to 
hurricane watches, but the threat of heavy rains remained along 
much of Mexico's coast. Tamaulipas residents were told to expect as 
much as eight to ten inches of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen Mexican ports along the Gulf were closed Friday to  
small and medium craft navigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bret crossed the hurricane threshold Friday with maximum  
sustained winds of 75 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	It is one of two major storms in the Atlantic. Late Saturday,  
Tropical Storm Cindy was 450 miles west of the Cape Verde Islands. 
It was moving west at 12 mph and had maximum sustained winds of 70 
mph, the Hurricane Center reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
