<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith's Agent To Talk With Bengals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Akili Smith's agent hopes that face-to-face  
meetings with the Cincinnati Bengals can break a contract impasse 
and get the first-round draft pick in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Leigh Steinberg plans to fly to Cincinnati on Sunday to  
jump-start negotiations, which have stalled over how Smith's 
contract will be structured. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback from Oregon was the third overall pick in the  
draft and is the highest pick left unsigned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like it's got to be more productive being in Cincinnati  
than sitting in California watching the days roll off the clock,'' 
Steinberg said Saturday. ``We're acutely aware of the passage of 
time. I very much want to conclude this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals welcomed his visit, but gave no indication they were  
willing to substantially change their offer of a contract tied to 
performance. Steinberg is seeking a contract closer to the one that 
Cleveland gave quarterback Tim Couch, chosen two spots ahead of 
Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hopeful we'll be able to get something done. Whether we  
do or not remains to be seen,'' said Katherine Blackburn, the 
team's executive vice president. ``But I do think it's a good 
step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides remain philosophically divided on how closely  
Smith's salary should be tied to performance. The Bengals gave 
contracts with voidable years to top draft picks Dan Wilkinson and 
Ki-Jana Carter earlier this decade and were unhappy with their 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg had little trouble negotiating those contracts. The  
impasse over Smith's contract has brought back memories of the 
protracted negotiations that cost quarterback David Klingler most 
of training camp in 1992. He also was a client of Steinberg's. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's as if the Bengals march to their own drummer in sort of  
unilaterally removing themselves from the remainder of the National 
Football League,'' Steinberg said. ``It's the Bermuda Triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here is a situation where we simply want Akili salaried in the  
same way that similarly situated quarterbacks have been in recent 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackburn welcomed the chance to go over the offers in person  
rather than over the phone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess we haven't been willing to necessarily do the Couch or  
(Ryan) Leaf deals and tried to explain to them the reasons why 
not,'' she said. ``We've tried to address the problems that come up 
with those contracts in a few different ways. So maybe we'll get a 
better chance to go over it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All along, the Bengals have envisioned Smith as a backup to Jeff  
Blake this season, which is the last of Blake's contract. Coach 
Bruce Coslet couldn't say Saturday whether Smith has missed too 
much practice time to allow him to be No. 2 once he signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody learns at a different pace,'' Coslet said. ``To say  
that at this point he could be the No. 2, I don't know. We'll have 
to see how fast he picks things up. This is all speculation right 
now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
