<DOCNO> APW19990821.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Mob Boss Expected To Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- No one knows just what the future of the  
Philadelphia mob will be now that reputed leader Joseph ``Skinny 
Joey'' Merlino is in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Merlino's alleged predecessor, Ralph Natale, producing  
a bombshell this week by reportedly agreeing to testify for 
prosecutors, the gangland landscape could change dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very unusual,'' Edwin Jacobs Jr., one of Merlino's  
attorneys, said Saturday. ``As far as I know, it's the first time a 
person identified as a head or a former head of an organized crime 
unit by the FBI has ever flipped sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Natale, who is currently in jail on federal drug conspiracy  
charges, has reportedly agreed to provide information on drug 
dealing, murders and political corruption in Philadelphia and 
Camden, N.J., after secretly meeting with federal authorities for 
about two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Such cooperation, reported this week by newspapers citing law  
enforcement officials, would make him the highest-ranking American 
Mafia figure ever to cooperate. It also marks a possible turning 
point for the future of the Philadelphia mob, which has endured a 
series of turncoats and other troubles in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ironically, one of the most outspoken critics of such a deal  
is Natale himself,'' Jacobs said. ``He's been very vocal in the 
past about using rats as government witnesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the last 13 years, nearly a dozen initiated or ``made''  
members of the local crime family have turned into government 
witnesses. It was mobster Ronald Previte, a top Natale associate, 
who wore a hidden wire provided by the FBI, that led to the arrests 
of Natale, Merlino and four other Boston mob associates on drug 
charges in June. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, internal divisions erupted into a mob war that almost  
led to the assassination of then underboss Merlino. And most 
recently, Joseph Anthony Ligambi emerged as the new mob boss after 
just two years in the organization, a sign of the vacuum in the 
power leadership, according to law enforcement officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, there's no true Mafia tradition practiced in  
Philadelphia anymore. There's just been an influx of younger men 
like Joey (Merlino) with no idea about how the traditional Mafia is 
supposed to be run,'' said mob criminologist and historian Celeste 
Morello, who lives in South Philadelphia. ``Many of the older men 
think 'This is not our Mafia anymore,' ... so there's no 'omerta' -- 
the Sicilian code of silence -- that's really been broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Natale has been quietly negotiating a deal with federal  
authorities since his arrest on federal drug charges two months 
ago, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported Friday. He has been held in 
the Salem County Jail in southern New Jersey on charges that he 
operated a methamphetamine distribution ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Natale, a former leader of the New Jersey Bartenders Union,  
allegedly headed the Philadelphia crime family for four years 
before he was jailed in June 1998 for alleged parole violations. He 
previously had served two consecutive sentences totaling 27 years 
for an arson insurance scam and drug trafficking convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of Natale's June arrest on drug charges, he was  
serving time at an Ohio federal prison for the parole violations. 
The parole violations stemmed from several meetings he had with 
convicted felons, including Merlino, in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is Ralph doesn't want to die in jail,'' one  
unidentified investigator told the Inquirer. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI refused to comment on the reported agreement Saturday,  
but Jacobs said he and Merlino believe it is true. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard ... he's been out of the federal court house in Camden  
meeting with the U.S. attorney and talking to FBI agents, 
apparently unbeknownst to his own attorney,'' Jacobs said. ``The 
only reason there can be is to cut a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Natale's attorney, Marc Neff, did not return telephone messages  
left at his office Saturday. He told the Inquirer in Friday's 
editions that he had heard the rumors but was unaware of any 
agreement. The assistant U.S. attorney handling the case, Barry 
Gross, also could not be reached for comment Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Natale is expected to corroborate some of the evidence and  
testimony offered by Previte, who recorded hundreds of 
conversations with mob figures for two years beginning in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
