<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 19:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Official Hurt in Cleveland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- NFL official Ron Liebsack suffered a broken leg  
and sprained knee Saturday night during the exhibition game between 
the Cleveland Browns and Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	Liebsack, a side judge covering the goal line, had thrown a  
penalty flag when Browns running back Terry Kirby fell out of 
bounds, rolling up on Liebsack's left leg. The accident occurred 
late in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Liebsack laid on the ground for a few minutes and was eventually  
carted off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby caught a pass from Browns quarterback Ty Detmer in the  
middle of the field, cut outside and was trying to break into the 
end zone when he hit Liebsack. The Browns were called for holding 
on the play. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 08:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Say Bush Passed 1st Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nightmare, painted by a rival: Republicans  
for George W. Bush wake up next year, in the middle of a 
presidential debate with the Democratic nominee, and realize their 
guy is unready and unfit. 
</P>
<P>
	That fear, Lamar Alexander's parting shot at the Texas governor,  
now has been quieted by the simple fact that Bush survived his 
first campaign crisis, said Tom Rath, a field operative of 
Alexander's defunct campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not a GOP jittery -- publicly, at least -- about its  
runaway front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Out in the real world, at the grass roots, ``people feel  
relieved to see that it wasn't a house of cards that was going to 
crumble, that he has some steel in him, he didn't go off into a 
snit,'' Rath said from New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what Lamar was asking. How will George W. do in a  
debate, where you get something thrown at you that you didn't 
expect,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rath, now uncommitted, may someday seek a job in the Bush  
operation. But his review of Bush's performance over the past week 
echoed in random checks with Republican activists and officials 
around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent firestorm will strengthen Bush, said Arkansas Gov.  
Mike Huckabee, who announced his endorsement of Bush in the middle 
of the three-day eruption. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll make him bulletproof,'' Huckabee said.  
</P>
<P>
	First, Bush angrily lashed out Wednesday at reporters pressing  
to know, based on no allegation, whether he had ever used cocaine. 
The next day, he showcased his composure by convening a news 
conference on the matter, only to contort his denials around a 
confusion of 15- or 25-year standards used to investigate the drug 
use of prospective White House employees. 
</P>
<P>
	By Friday, Bush was back on message: My past is nobody's  
business as long as I've learned from my mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	A Time-CNN poll released Friday backed his assertion. Fully 84  
percent of Americans surveyed said any cocaine use in his 20s 
should not disqualify Bush from being president. And of the 54 
percent who were aware of the unsubstantiated talk about Bush and 
cocaine, half thought the governor had handled it well. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansans ``are saying that if this country let Bill Clinton  
take a walk, not with allegations but with admissions of wrongdoing 
..., I'll be doggoned if I'm going to let the press and the 
opposition party take down a man for something that hasn't even 
been alleged,'' said Huckabee. 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois freshman Rep. Judy Biggert said she was at a state  
Capitol event with the Young Republicans, and all the sour talk 
there was about the news media, not Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're really tired of the press and the media really  
hounding candidates,'' she said. ``What we see is just that the 
press is looking for any chink in the armor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has not yet made a presidential  
endorsement and has sounded supportive not only of Bush but of his 
rivals John McCain and Elizabeth Dole. On Thursday, he defended 
Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree with the separation of a person's private life from  
their public duties,'' said the mayor, who has faced public 
questions about his marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'm interested in is what kind of job did he do as  
governor of Texas. I think he's done a great job as governor of 
Texas,'' said Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jim DeMint, at the close of a week traveling his South  
Carolina district, said: ``I just hear, `Leave the guy alone.' I 
think he's setting a pretty good precedent about questions like 
this. If a credible person wants to come forward and challenge his 
integrity ..., he should answer it. But if it's just an abstract 
question, he's doing the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeMint, another freshman, added that the controversy will help  
Bush's image. ``He's not sensitive,'' DeMint said. ``He's still 
smiling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield Nelson, a Republican national committeeman in Little  
Rock, Ark., said the only jitters within the party are coming from 
Bush's primary rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``His opponents would like for us to think that (some  
nervousness) is now taking place out there,'' Nelson said. 
``They're grasping for straws.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
