<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles' Clark Likely Out for Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- First baseman Will Clark will undergo surgery  
on his left elbow next week and will almost certainly be lost to 
the Baltimore Orioles for the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore placed Clark on the 15-day disabled list Saturday.  
Clark, who has not played since Aug. 13, will have bone chips 
removed from his elbow during an operation planned for Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Apparently one of them has become lodged in the elbow and is  
keeping it from getting any better. Actually it's gotten worse 
lately,'' Orioles general manager Frank Wren said. ``We want to go 
ahead and get it done so going into next year we'll know he's fine. 
It's probably a four- to six-week procedure, especially for a 
position player. It will more than likely end his season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To fill Clark's place on the roster, Baltimore purchased the  
contract of outfielder Derrick May from Triple-A Rochester. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old Clark was able to swing a bat this week but had  
difficulty throwing a ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``About two weeks ago he started to have discomfort in his  
elbow. He kind of played through it, but it got to the point where 
he couldn't get through it,'' Wren said. ``He got an injection in 
the elbow to cool it down. Unfortunately, over the last four days 
it not only didn't cool it down, but it's gotten worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clark has been bothered by elbow problems throughout his 14-year  
career. Taped to his locker is a picture of several bone chips 
removed from his elbow during a previous operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been dealing with this since 1986. I've played my whole  
big league career with a broken elbow,'' he said. ``This not only 
affects my baseball play, it affects my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clark hoped the cortisone shot would help, but it had little  
effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got the shot because I wanted it to calm down because I  
wanted to finish up the season. It wouldn't allow me to do that,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark left little doubt that his target date for returning is  
the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I have (surgery) now I can come back to the team and start  
rehabbing immediately. That would put me in a better position to be 
ready for next season,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark signed a two-year, $11 million contract during the  
offseason. Asked to take over for the departed Rafael Palmeiro at 
first base, he has driven in only 29 runs in 77 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark has been on the disabled list seven times over the past  
four seasons. He missed a month earlier this year after breaking 
his thumb trying to field a grounder off the turf in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Conine will become the Orioles' everyday first baseman.  
</P>
<P>
	May, a nine-year veteran, was signed by the Orioles on June 3  
and assigned to Rochester. He hit .270 with five homers and 41 RBIs 
in 70 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
