<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Entering Gourmet Soda Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Miller Brewing Co. is entering the gourmet soda  
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's second-biggest brewer is assuming control of root  
beer, vanilla cream and orange cream produced under the Henry 
Weinhard's brand name. It acquired the sodas in April through its 
purchase of certain brands from the Stroh Brewery Co. 
</P>
<P>
	It marks the first time Miller has produced non-alcoholic  
beverages -- except for Sharp's, its non-alcoholic beer -- since the 
repeal of Prohibition. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's two largest rivals, Anheuser-Busch Inc. and Adolph  
Coors Co., do not produce sodas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We view it as an opportunity,'' Miller spokeswoman Susan  
Henderson said Friday. She said the Weinhard sodas have had strong 
sales growth into this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The sodas are higher-prices specialty products sold primarily in  
Oregon, Washington and California. Miller plans limited 
distribution in other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller last month hired new advertising agencies for its Miller  
Lite and Miller Genuine Draft beer as sales of its two biggest 
brands continued to slump. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Picnic Draws 7,000-plus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VASHON, Wash.(AP) -- More than 7,000 people turned out Saturday  
to hear Republican presidential hopefuls Elizabeth Dole and John 
McCain stump at the GOP Picnic, a gala rivaling the recent Iowa 
Straw Poll in orchestration and glitz. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual gathering appeared undimmed by host Thomas Stewart's  
$5 million penalty last year for campaign-finance violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kids were entertained by clowns and at a play park made of  
gigantic inflated animals, while their parents devoured free 
burgers and hot dogs. The crowd gave standing ovations to both 
candidates during the event at Stewart's cattle ranch on Vashon 
Island, about five miles west of Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a wonderful victory for me in Iowa,'' Dole told the  
crowd. She finished third in the non-binding straw poll Aug. 14 
behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush and publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not spend millions of dollars, and it was pretty much a  
four-month effort,'' Dole said. Her campaign is relatively young, 
she said, because she undertook no political activity while she was 
president of the American Red Cross, a post she left in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole criticized the Clinton administration on several points,  
especially for what she described as its ineffective drug-control 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore ``have been AWOL  
when it comes to stopping the flow of illegal drugs,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also criticized what she said were falling standards in  
education and, without mentioning any of Clinton's personal 
troubles specifically, repeatedly called for honesty and integrity 
at the highest level. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am willing to lead by example to affirm and promote those  
things that are right,'' Dole said. She emphasized her leadership 
experience from serving as President Reagan's secretary of 
transportation, as President Bush's secretary of labor and as head 
of the Red Cross. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said she favors a tax cut, local control of public schools  
and increased military preparedness, including stepped-up efforts 
toward a missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. McCain, R-Ariz., opened with a bit of self-deprecating  
humor regarding his six years as a prisoner of war in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to remind you, it doesn't take a lot of talent to  
get shot down,'' he said. ``I intercepted a surface-to-air missile 
with my jet airplane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His booth on the ranch grounds featured a larger-than-life photo  
of a much younger McCain in his Navy pilot's jump suit. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain hammered on the themes of campaign-finance reform,  
increased military salaries and readiness, tax reform and local 
educational control. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a weak and hollow military,'' he said. ``We have  
11,000 military families on food stamps, and that has got to 
stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Dole, he called for increased efforts toward developing a  
missile-defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Event host Stewart, Washington's largest contributor to  
Republican campaigns, pleaded guilty in March 1998 to laundering 
contributions through employees of Food Services of America, a 
subsidiary of his Seattle-based holding company, Services Group of 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart was fined $5 million, placed on home detention and  
ordered to perform community service. He declined to be interviewed 
Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
