<DOCNO> APW19990821.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K Glitches With Navigation Tool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- It appeared to be smooth sailing  
Saturday for boaters and aviators who rely on a satellite-based 
navigation system that reset itself, which was expected to confuse 
older locator units. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Coast Guard here and the Federal Aviation  
Administration reported receiving no calls for stranded boats or 
airplanes having problems in determining their coordinates by using 
the Global Positioning System, or GPS. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just a regular weekend. It's actually been a very slow day,''  
said Coast Guard Chief Petty Officer Danny Phee. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA in Washington also had no reports of problems, said  
agency spokesman Les Dorr, noting that small, private plane pilots 
had been warned to check their systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Time clocks on the popular GPS receivers reset to zero at 5 p.m.  
PDT Saturday, which could possibly confuse units made before 1993. 
Those units may take longer to pinpoint a location, be off in their 
calculations, or be unable to find the location. 
</P>
<P>
	GPS receivers determine location by using signals of three to 24  
satellites. To do this they need the exact time, which the system 
determines by counting the weeks since Jan. 5, 1980 -- up to 1,024. 
But GPS reached its maximum number of weeks on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers offer upgrades. Otherwise, some receivers may  
think it is 1980 when the clock reset, according to the 
Transportation Department. 
</P>
<P>
	GPS, originally designed for the military, is booming in the  
commercial market, often offered in luxury cars as a mapping 
device. Aviators and boaters have been using GPS for at least a 
decade and only in recent years have hikers begun to use hand-held 
units. 
</P>
<P>
	A nationwide, private tow boat agency, Vessel Assist Association  
of America, based in Newport Beach, reported no GPS-related 
problems Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Definitely not. We haven't had any troubles at all,'' said  
Steve Ryan, a dispatcher for Vessel Assist. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 16:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Biographer: Sagan Smoked Marijuana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The late astronomer and author Carl Sagan  
was a secret but avid marijuana smoker, crediting it with inspiring 
essays and scientific insight, according to Sagan's biographer. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the pseudonym ``Mr. X'', Sagan wrote about his pot smoking  
in an essay published in the 1971 book ``Reconsidering Marijuana.'' 
The book's editor, Lester Grinspoon, recently disclosed the secret 
to Sagan's biographer, Keay Davidson. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson, a writer for the San Francisco Examiner, revealed the  
marijuana use in an article published in the newspaper's magazine 
Sunday. ``Carl Sagan: A Life'' is due out in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find that today a single joint is enough to get me high ...  
in one movie theater recently I found I could get high just by 
inhaling the cannabis smoke which permeated the theater,'' wrote 
Sagan, who authored popular science books such as ``Cosmos,'' 
``Contact,'' and ``The Dragons of Eden.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the essay, Sagan said marijuana inspired some of his  
intellectual work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can remember one occasion, taking a shower with my wife  
while high, in which I had an idea on the origins and invalidities 
of racism in terms of gaussian distribution curves,'' wrote the 
former Cornell University professor. ``I wrote the curves in soap 
on the shower wall, and went to write the idea down. 
</P>
<P>
	Sagan also wrote that pot enhanced his experience of food,  
particularly potatoes, music and sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Grinspoon, Sagan's closest friend for 30 years, said Sagan's  
marijuana use is evidence against the notion that marijuana makes 
people less ambitious. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was certainly highly motivated to work, to contribute,''  
said Grinspoon, a psychiatry professor at Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Grinspoon is an advocate of decriminalizing marijuana.  
</P>
<P>
	Ann Druyan, Sagan's former wife, is a director of the National  
Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws. The nonprofit group 
promotes legalization of marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Sagan died of pneumonia in 1996. He was 62.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:48:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Glitch Delays Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) -- Air traffic controllers had to rely on  
memory to guide airplanes during a computer problem that also 
delayed scores of flights across the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	A new computer system was down for about three hours, forcing  
delays of up to 90 minutes for nearly 140 flights at five airports 
Thursday morning, the Federal Aviation Administration said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the computer failure has not been determined.  
</P>
<P>
	The computer at the Los Angeles Air Route Traffic Control Center  
in Palmdale guides flights north of the U.S.-Mexico border, over 
central California, Nevada and the Pacific Ocean. It failed at 5:07 
a.m. and was fully restored at 8:05 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA spokesman Mitch Barker in Seattle said controllers relied on  
their memories to identify planes on their screen and they were 
guided to their destinations. 
</P>
<P>
	No airplanes were in danger, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Palmdale center is the fifth in the United States to begin  
using the new computer system installed last year as part of a 
nationwide $425 million FAA modernization. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 21:03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Kills 17 in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- A bomb exploded at a party south of the  
capital, killing 17 people, including two children, and wounding 12 
others, security officials said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bomb was thrown into the middle of a celebration late Friday  
in the small town of Ouzera, 60 miles south of the coastal capital, 
Algiers, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one claimed responsibility for the attack. Authorities have  
blamed recurring violence on Islamic insurgents, who have been 
fighting to topple the government of the northern Africa country 
since 1992. That was the year the military-backed government 
canceled elections that the Islamic Salvation Front was set to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's attack came just after President Abdelaziz Bouteflika  
had called a national referendum for Sept. 16 on a peace plan 
intended to end the insurgency. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his election in April, Bouteflika has taken several steps  
to end the conflict, including acknowledging officially that 
100,000 people had been killed in the insurgency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Medea region, near to the attack site in Ouzera, is  
considered to be the territory of Armed Islamic Group leader Antar 
Zouabri, who has rejected Bouteflika's policies. 
</P>
<P>
	The radical Armed Islamic Group has claimed responsibility for  
many massacres since the insurgency began. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 10:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Actress Bids for U.S. Archery Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Geena Davis found out she was a good  
shot on a movie set. 
</P>
<P>
	The 43-year-old actress is now ranked 22nd in the nation in  
women's archery and is competing this weekend to qualify for the 
next Olympic team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have learned as an adult that I'm fairly athletic,'' Davis  
said Friday as she practiced for semifinals of the U.S. Olympic 
trials, which began this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The star of ``Thelma and Louise'' and ``The Accidental Tourist''  
-- for which she won an Oscar in 1988 -- has surprised archers with 
her quick rise in a sport that doesn't normally capture much 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Camera crews on Friday surrounded Davis, wearing a floppy blue  
hat and sunglasses, as she calmly fired off 60 arrows to a target 
70 meters away. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she would make the team, it would be unbelievable for our  
sport,'' said Denise Parker, the top-ranked woman in the nation. 
``The question is, does she want to be in the spotlight in this 
environment?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis discovered she had great aim while training to fire  
handguns for her part as an assassin in 1996's ``The Long Kiss 
Goodnight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She kept her hobby a secret from Hollywood and the public,  
despite winning a tournament or two, until she finished 29th out of 
300 women in Ohio to qualify for the Olympic semifinals. Four of 
the 32 semifinalists dropped out, making Davis one of 28 competing 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	That number will drop by Monday to eight women who will compete  
next month in California for three team spots and one alternate 
spot at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' coach Don Rabska, an archer for more than 30 years, said  
she has mastered a concentration during her acting career that 
helps her as an archer. Archery, he said, is all about finesse and 
mental toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis has been practicing five hours a day, shooting about 300  
arrows. She had a target range set up on the set of her latest 
film, ``Stuart Little.'' She also goes to the gym five days a week 
to work out on the treadmill and lift weights. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Davis: ``I don't feel that I've yet discovered how good I  
can get.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990821.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 10:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
