<HEADLINE> Water Leak Closes Malibu, Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos    	
</P>
<P>
	MALIBU, Calif. (AP) -- Ritzy eateries and other businesses stood  
empty Saturday at the peak of the summer beach-going season in this 
star-studded enclave as officials turned people away and repaired a 
leaky water main that left the town dry. 
</P>
<P>
	As the morning fog lifted, ``CLOSED'' signs hung in the darkened  
windows and parking spaces abounded along normally jammed Malibu 
streets, home to the rich and famous, including Barbra Streisand, 
Johnny Carson and Martin Sheen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing fine without water; I'm not doing well without  
customers,'' said Carter Crary, owner of Malibu Divers, a small 
shop on the Pacific Coast Highway, Malibu's main thoroughfare. 
Crary said he expected to lose ``thousands and thousands'' of 
dollars over the dry weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the street, the football-sized parking lot at Duke's  
restaurant and bar stood empty. A sign in the window read: ``Due to 
the current lack of water in Malibu, Duke's is unable to open for 
business at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaks, caused by natural land movement, were found in the water  
main Thursday. Officials turned off the system, depleting reserves 
by Friday night. The lack of water forced the closure of a 20-mile 
stretch of Pacific Coast Highway from Topanga Canyon Road to Los 
Posas Road at Point Mugu for health and safety reasons, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The road may remain closed until Wednesday, said Los Angeles  
County fire Capt. Steve Valenzuela. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 5,000 residents and businesses along this 27-mile-long  
strip of beachfront paradise, lined with multimillion-dollar homes, 
went without water overnight and were encouraged to boil water once 
faucets began flowing again late Saturday, said Melinda Barrett, 
spokeswoman with the county's public works department. 
</P>
<P>
	A steady stream of BMWs and Volvos pulled up to a parking lot at  
Pepperdine University -- one of two sites where county officials 
distributed free 5-gallon jugs of drinking water. A row of 20 tall, 
green port-a-potties offered some relief to the wealth and the 
less-fortunate alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``Malibuites are tough,'' said Mary Fitzgerald, a 30-year  
resident, as she loaded water tanks for her horses in the trunk of 
her Volvo. ``It's inconvenient, but it's doable.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
