<HEADLINE> Gun Dealer Seeks McVeigh Firearm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A gun dealer wants a piece of history -- the  
pistol that Timothy McVeigh had when he was stopped for a traffic 
violation after the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal 
Building. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Livingston, owner of Pat's Pawn and Gun in Ogden, Kan., sold  
the .45-caliber Glock pistol and a TEC-9 pistol to McVeigh before 
the 1995 bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	He says McVeigh wrote a bad check to pay him $291.22 for the  
TEC-9, and a small-claims court judge in Riley County, Kan., 
awarded him $450.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for McVeigh sought to settle for $332, but Livingston  
sent back their check. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want anybody else's money,'' Livingston told The Daily  
Oklahoman on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	What he does want, Livingston said, is the Glock, since McVeigh  
apparently no longer owned the TEC-9 when he was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Livingston plans to file a lien with the federal government  
asking that the Glock be released from evidence as payment of 
McVeigh's debt to him. However, McVeigh's conviction is still under 
appeal and evidence generally remains in court custody until all 
appeals are final. 
</P>
<P>
	``He owes me, not these ... attorneys or anybody else,''  
Livingston said. ``He bought a gun. So, to me, it's fair that I get 
a gun back and that (the Glock) is the only one he owns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the bombing on April 19, 1995, which killed 168  
people, a state trooper stopped McVeigh because his car had no tag, 
then arrested him after finding the Glock in McVeigh's jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it's the most valuable gun in the world because it  
caught him,'' Livingston said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
