<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Say Riggleman Stays for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs general manager Ed Lynch tried to  
end rumors that manager Jim Riggleman would be fired by committing 
to Riggleman through the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim Riggleman is going to manage this club and we're going to  
evaluate the situation at the end of the season,'' Lynch said 
before Saturday's game between the Cubs and Colorado Rockies. 
``Hopefully we'll play to a level in the next few weeks where this 
is a dead issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riggleman's job status has been rumored to be in jeopardy  
because of the team's dramatic downslide. The Cubs were 32-23 
entering play on June 9 and in second place in the NL Central. 
Since then, the Cubs have gone 19-46 for a 51-69 overall record and 
last in the division. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a distraction to me,'' Riggleman said of the rumors.  
``I think it might have been a distraction for some of the players. 
We've all got a chance in the next five weeks to earn our 
stripes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs players welcomed Lynch's announcement.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's very smart by Ed Lynch to stop the distraction,''  
Chicago's Sammy Sosa said. ``Every day we came here and heard the 
rumors. That's a great decision (to keep Riggleman). He's a great 
manager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're losing, that's constantly going to be asked and  
talked about,'' said first baseman Mark Grace. 
</P>
<P>
	Is Riggleman responsible for the team's poor play?  
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely not,'' Grace said. ``His players just haven't done  
the job for him. Why? I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one could have predicted pitchers Steve Trachsel going 4-14  
or Kevin Tapani falling to 6-11 or closer Rod Beck, pitcher Kerry 
Wood and leadoff batter Lance Johnson getting hurt, or Gary Gaetti 
batting a feeble .188, Grace said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know how much these guys are dying,'' Grace said. ``What can  
you do? Go out, be professional and battle your butt off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grace did his part to motivate his teammates. On Saturday, he  
posted a note that he would reward players but only if the team 
wins. A home run is worth $100, an RBI $50, a hit $20, a run scored 
$50 and moving runners up $10. Beck will pay pitchers $100 for each 
win, $100 for each save, $50 for a hold, $20 for a strikeout and 
$20 for a double play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing else has been motivating the boys,'' Grace said. ``The  
key is only in wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs have not seen too many of those.  
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, we still have to go out and play well,''  
said second baseman Mickey Morandini. 
</P>
<P>
	Which is what Lynch and Riggleman are looking for.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
