<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Comets Carry On Without Perrot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Coach Van Chancellor remembers the day  
Kim Perrot showed up to open tryouts for the Houston Comets. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-5 point guard out of Southwestern Louisiana hadn't  
been taken in the WNBA draft, and Chancellor didn't think she was 
as good as those who had. 
</P>
<P>
	But Perrot stood out among 150 people in the sweaty high school  
gym. 
</P>
<P>
	``You brought your 15 best friends and put them every 20 feet  
around the court,'' Chancellor told her. ``Everywhere I went, you 
heard them say, `I know you're going to keep Kim Perrot, coach.''' 
</P>
<P>
	And he did, inviting Perrot and another player to training camp.  
</P>
<P>
	But Chancellor still wasn't convinced Perrot could do the job.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought she was a little wild,'' he said. ``She thought I  
was a conservative Mississippi coach who didn't appreciate the 
flair for the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He brought in other point guards, but Perrot outplayed them and  
was signed as a developmental player. She was promoted to the 
Comets' active roster in June 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went through half a season yanking her in and out. She never  
did quit me or get mad,'' Chancellor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot didn't give up off the court, either.  
</P>
<P>
	She was diagnosed with lung cancer in February. Eventually the  
cancer spread to her brain and after a seven-month battle, she died 
Thursday in Houston. Perrot was 32. 
</P>
<P>
	She helped the Comets win consecutive WNBA championships and in  
the process became what Chancellor called the best defensive player 
in the league, despite never winning the defensive award. 
</P>
<P>
	``But no question in my mind, for two years running the best at  
stopping the ball,'' he said. ``She could guard 94 feet better than 
anybody I've coached.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Comets played their first game Friday night since Perrot's  
death, losing 68-64 to the Los Angeles Sparks after rallying to tie 
the game with two minutes left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very proud of the Comets,'' Chancellor said. ``We just  
fought and played our heart out and did everything that you humanly 
could do to win a game under the most difficult conditions ever in 
the history of women's basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Cynthia Cooper, Perrot's best friend, chose not to play  
and didn't dress. The league's two-time MVP missed her first game 
in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely missed her not playing, but at the same time,  
given the circumstances, we were just glad that she came,'' said 
Comets forward Sheryl Swoopes, who scored 25 points. ``She 
definitely helped us get through this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Comets had a game Saturday night at Sacramento.  
</P>
<P>
	Many in the Forum crowd of 13,116 -- largest of the season -- wore  
a snippet of white ribbon above their hearts in Perrot's memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Several fans displayed hand-lettered signs saluting Perrot. One  
read ``Kim Perrot, 4Ever in Our Hearts.'' Another read ``Go Comets 
Go. May you have strength and fortitude. Our prayers are with 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot was remembered in a brief halftime video that opened with  
her stealing the ball and scoring on a fingertip roll. Her smile 
was prominent in highlights from last season's WNBA championship 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kim was a wonderful person,'' Comets reserve center Tammy  
Jackson said. ``You can't take away the energy that she brought to 
this team, the love she brought to this team. She was something 
special to each individual person. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what the mood was, you knew Kim was going to come in  
and try to bring a smile or get you to laugh. It's going to be 
missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A public service to celebrate Perrot's life will be held Monday  
at Second Baptist Church in Houston, with several players 
participating. She will be buried Tuesday in her hometown of 
Lafayette, La. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when the team might recover from its grief, Chancellor  
said it would be a ``long time, when you lose someone like her.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
